('245', '87', 'assistant', '## Detailed Report: Supervisor Drill-Down Processes for RM Performance\n\n### Introduction\n\nIn the competitive world of wealth management, understanding and optimizing the performance of Relationship Managers (RMs) is crucial. Supervisors need efficient tools to drill down from high-level summaries to detailed performance metrics. This report outlines how supervisors can navigate dashboards effectively to gain insights into RM performance.\n\n### High-Level Leads Overview\n\nThe process begins at the **Supervisor Dashboard**, which displays a consolidated leads summary widget. This widget provides an aggregate view of all leads managed by the RMs reporting to a supervisor. Key data displayed include:\n\n- Total number of leads\n- Status-wise lead distribution, such as:\n  - New\n  - Ready for Follow-Up\n  - In Progress\n  - Client Accepted\n  - Client Rejected\n\n### Drill-Down Mechanism\n\n##### Opening the Detailed View\n\nTo access a more detailed view:\n\n1. **Dashboard Interaction:** Locate the Leads summary widget.\n2. **Initiating Drill-Down:** Click the **“More”** or equivalent icon (often depicted as three dots) to reveal additional options.\n3. **Navigate to Detailed View:** This interaction opens the **“Lead Status by RM”** dashboard, offering a more granular view of RM performance.\n\n#### Viewing RM-Wise Performance\n\nThe **Lead Status by RM** view displays:\n\n- **Rows for Each RM:** Detailed performance metrics for each RM, including their name and specific lead counts.\n- **Status Breakdown:** For each RM, categorize leads by status:\n  - New Leads\n  - Ready for Follow-Up\n  - In Progress\n  - Client Accepted\n  - Client Rejected\n\n#### Filtering and Search\n\n**Filter Capabilities:**\n\n- Use the **search bar** at the top of the table to refine results by typing an RM’s name.\n- Provides targeted insights into an individual RM’s performance by isolating their data.\n\n### Best Practices for Supervisors\n\n#### Efficient Dashboard Use\n\n- **Customize Views:** Supervisors should customize dashboard widgets to prioritize frequently accessed data.\n- **Regular Monitoring:** Consistent monitoring aids in early identification of patterns and potential issues.\n  \n#### Enhancing RM Performance\n\n- **Performance Reviews:** Utilize detailed views for in-depth performance reviews during RM assessments.\n- **Target Setting:** Establish clear targets for RMs based on historical data and performance metrics.\n\n### Industry Insights and Best Practices\n\n- Financial institutions increasingly use real-time dashboards for dynamic performance tracking.\n- Advanced machine learning models are being integrated to predict performance outcomes and suggest RM strategies.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe ability to transition from a high-level leads overview to detailed RM performance metrics empowers supervisors to make informed, data-driven decisions. By leveraging dashboard functionality effectively, supervisors can enhance team productivity and manage client relationships more efficiently.\n\n### Sources & References\n\nNo external sources were used in this report; it is developed based on internal processes and expert insights.\n\n### Limitations\n\nThis report is based on general best practices and assumed dashboard functionalities. Specific implementations may vary depending on the institution''s software and systems in use. Future enhancements might come from increased integration with AI tools and improved user interface options.', 'resp_010cd76aeed48c370069424a61499081979c03c6bd65231325', NULL, '{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"conversation","confidence":1,"matchedKeywords":[]},"jobId":"job_1765952098094_rebazi2et","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_010cd76aeed48c370069424a61499081979c03c6bd65231325","reportFormat":"Custom","mode":"deep","answeredAt":"2025-12-17T06:42:23.350Z"}', '2025-12-17 06:14:58.03792'),
('254', '94', 'user', 'How does risk profiling work in the system?', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-12-17 12:05:57.588738'),
('255', '94', 'assistant', '# Risk profiling in the system: end-to-end view ## 1. Overview - Risk profiling is a configurable, questionnaire-driven mechanism used to determine a customer’s risk appetite and assign a risk profile based on questionnaire scores. Every customer has a risk appetite, and the application decides the risk profile by aggregating the questionnaire results. This configuration of risk profiling and risk appetite is explicitly described in the risk framework documents. [1] ## 2. Data inputs - Core inputs include customer data, risk questionnaires, and risk appetite mappings used to establish how responses map to a risk profile. Risk appetite mapping resources (grid/mappings) are used to align questionnaire scores with corresponding risk levels. [5] - The risk questionnaire itself contains fields and structure used to collect customer responses (question descriptions, mandatory flags, multi-select options, scoring types, computation types, and score ranges). [2] - Question definitions and scoring rules (e.g., None vs Range scoring, Sum computation, and range-based scoring) are standard across implementations. [7] ## 3. Questionnaire configuration and flow - Users can create and configure risk profile questionnaires within the application, including setting up questions, mandatory flags, multi-select options, scoring types, and calculation logic. Screen: Create a new risk profile questionnaire. [1] - Each question supports various attributes such as Mandatory Type, Multi Select, Scoring Type (None/Range), Computation Type (Sum), and from/to score ranges with an associated final Score. [2] - The risk questionnaire structure supports additional elements like warnings, acknowledgements, and disclaimers to be presented during profiling. [2] ## 4. Scoring rules and mapping - Scoring can be configured per question as None or Range, with a Sum computation for aggregating responses across questions. Range-type scoring maps specific response ranges to a final score. [7] - The aggregated scores from the questionnaire feed into a risk appetite/risk profile mapping to produce a final risk rating for the customer. This linkage between questionnaire scores and risk appetite is described in risk profiling configurations. [1] ## 5. Validations and governance - The system enforces governance checks during profiling and transaction processing, including general validations and KYC-related validations (e.g., mandatory fields, length checks, and KYC status gating). [4] - There are risk-profile-specific validations in order-flow scenarios, such as ensuring a risk profile exists and is current; otherwise, certain actions (purchase, switch, SIP) may be disallowed. If the risk profile is expired, related actions are blocked; if no risk profile is present, actions are blocked. [3] ## 6. Storage and ownership of risk data - Risk profiles are surfaced and managed within the customer and RM dashboards, reflecting risk-based grouping and visibility (e.g., customers grouped by risk profile, tracked by AUM). This governance/monitoring is shown in RM dashboards and customer dashboards. [13] - Risk appetite mappings and questionnaire configurations are stored as part of the risk framework, enabling mapping between questionnaire results and risk brackets. [5] ## 7. System modules and screens involved - The risk profiling configuration and execution involve modules such as the risk questionnaire designer (screen for creating risk profile questionnaires) and the PMS/Intellect integration points used to read/write risk-related data during transactions. Screens and flows for risk questionnaires are described in risk profiling journey documents. [1] - The risk profile framework is implemented across multiple platforms (e.g., Intellect, HSBC PWS), with cross-system orchestration to enforce risk constraints during order placement and portfolio actions. [2] ## 8. How the risk profile drives portfolio decisions and approvals - Product risk checks are performed against customer risk; if product risk exceeds customer risk, a notification is generated to alert the user. This gating ensures alignment between customer risk capacity and product selections. [3] - If a risk profile is expired, or if a customer does not have a risk profile, certain actions (Purchase/Switch/SIP) are disallowed, enforcing governance over portfolio changes. [3] - Risk-profile data also informs RM dashboards and customer composition analyses, enabling awareness and governance by risk tier when reviewing portfolios. [16] ## 9. In practice: a high-level flow - Create/configure a risk profile questionnaire (questions, scoring rules, mandatory fields). [1] - Collect customer responses and compute a risk score (sum or range-based computation). [7] - Map the score to a risk appetite/risk profile using predefined risk appetite mappings. [5] - Enforce governance: ensure KYC status is valid, and prevent actions if risk profile is missing or expired. [4] - Reflect and monitor the result in dashboards (customer RM views, risk-profile-based grouping). [16] ## Sources - JBR_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV1.pdf [1] - HSBC_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV1.pdf [2] - HSBC_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV10_Part 1.pdf [3] - 360One_Journey of Assesing Risk_V10_CCV15.pdf [4] - SBI International_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV1.pdf [5]', '270b3461-76d8-408f-91de-64bca03bf16d', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["risk profiling","Customer Risk profile","Product risk profile","Risk Appetite Mapping","Risk Rating","Risk Profile Questionnaire","Intellect","HSBC PWS","PMS application","KYC status validation"],"seed_node_ids":["system:pms_app","aum:risk_profiling","compliance:risk_profiling","dataentity:risk_rating","dataentity:customer","dataentity:risk_profiling","dataentity:risk_appetite_mapping","aum:customer_risk_profile","dataentity:risk_profile_questionnaire","system:intellect","compliance:ky