('32', '10', 'assistant', '# **KG + VectorStore Answer - Context: This is a follow-up question in a conversation. Please maintain context from the previous discussion.\n\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\n\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\n\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., "this", "it", "that", "these", "the above")\n• If such references exist, identify what they refer to based on the conversation history\n• Internally clarify the question to make it self-contained and explicit\n\nSTEP 2 - Focused Response Generation:\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\n\nUser''s Question: what is the diffrence between CRR and PRRR**\n\n_Generated: 2025-10-22 08:46_\n\n## **Answer**\n\n**Direct Answer:** CRR is the Customer Risk Profile <sup><a href="#cite-2">[2]</a></sup>. PRR is the Product Risk Profile <sup><a href="#cite-6">[6]</a></sup>. PRR equals CRR plus 2 for a warning scenario <sup><a href="#cite-6">[6]</a></sup>. If PRR exceeds CRR plus 2, a hard stop applies <sup><a href="#cite-6">[6]</a></sup>. <sup><a href="#cite-1">[1]</a></sup>\n\n**Key Points:**\n• Point 1: CRR stands for Customer Risk Profile <sup><a href="#cite-2">[2]</a></sup>  \n• Point 2: PRR stands for Product Risk Profile <sup><a href="#cite-6">[6]</a></sup>  \n• Point 3: PRR = CRR + 2 triggers a warning; PRR > CRR + 2 triggers a hard stop <sup><a href="#cite-6">[6]</a></sup> <sup><a href="#cite-1">[1]</a></sup>\n\n**Note:** CRR and PRR describe separate risk dimensions; CRR is customer risk, PRR is product risk <sup><a href="#cite-6">[6]</a></sup>.\n\n---\n\n## **Citations**\n\n<a id="cite-1"></a>\n**[1]** → **PMS MST Standardization.txt**\n\n<a id="cite-2"></a>\n**[2]** → **PAD PMS Reports & Statements_Final.pdf**\n\n<a id="cite-3"></a>\n**[3]** → **PAD risk profile & asset allocation - TH.pdf**\n\n<a id="cite-4"></a>\n**[4]** → **PAD PMS Reports & Statements_Final [v1].pdf**\n\n<a id="cite-5"></a>\n**[5]** → **Journey of Assessing Risk_Base_V1.0.pdf**\n\n<a id="cite-6"></a>\n**[6]** → **WQ_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF  V1.0_SBI_...**\n\n\n---\n\n## **Sources by File**\n\n- **Journey of Assessing Risk_Base_V1.0.pdf** → [5]\n- **PAD PMS Reports & Statements_Final [v1].pdf** → [4]\n- **PAD PMS Reports & Statements_Final.pdf** → [2]\n- **PAD risk profile & asset allocation - TH.pdf** → [3]\n- **PMS MST Standardization.txt** → [1]\n- **WQ_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF  V1.0_SBI_...** → [6]\n', 'f28d889f-5582-4d29-bcf9-dd21bd8962ac', '[{"filename":"PMS MST Standardization.txt","file_id":"file-Late1dSweSVymhi1uQ9XEM","score":0.7605547464414252,"text":"\\"Yes\\"     NaN             NaN        NaN\\n           3                   NaN               Answer 2 - Question 1        NaN                                            \\"No\\"     NaN             NaN        NaN\\n           4                   NaN               Answer 3 - Question 1        NaN                                \\"Not Applicable\\"     NaN             NaN        NaN\\n           5                   NaN               Text field Question 2        NaN      Question two for the switching declaration     NaN             NaN        NaN\\n           6                   NaN               Answer 1 - Question 2        NaN \\"Changes in investment strategy and/or exposure     NaN             NaN        NaN\\n           7                   NaN               Answer 2 - Question 2        NaN                                           \\"TBD\\"     NaN             NaN        NaN\\n           8                   NaN               Answer 3 - Question 2        NaN                                           \\"TBD\\"     NaN             NaN        NaN\\n           9...","query":"Context: This is a follow-up question in a conversation. Please maintain context from the previous discussion.\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"these\\", \\"the above\\")\\n• If such references exist, identify what they refer to based on the conversation history\\n• Internally clarify the question to make it self-contained and explicit\\n\\nSTEP 2 - Focused Response Generation:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: what is the diffrence between CRR and PRRR process workflow steps","norm_score":1,"relevance_score":0.5424166689922953},{"filename":"PAD PMS Reports & Statements_Final.pdf","file_id":"file-M1BsTmWWZbwS2Y4Kyz5sDX","score":0.7574382677856005,"text":"Corporate Customer: Company Name in English alphabet \\nCustomer Name (TH) [Applicable to Thailand]\\n\\nIndividual Customer: Full Name in Thai Text\\n\\nCorporate Customer: Company Name in Thai Text\\n\\nCustomer Segment\\n[Indicator]\\nMass/ Prime / Preferred/ Private / Corporate (as reflected in Country \\nSource Data)\\n\\nCurrent Risk Profile\\nCurrent Risk Profile Result (Outcome of Questionnaire)\\n- Defensive/Aggressive/etc..\\n\\nPrevious Risk Profile\\nPrevious Risk Profile Result (Outcome of Questionnaire)\\n- Defensive/Aggressive/etc..\\n\\nTagged Sales Staff ID Staff ID (as reflected in source) of staff customer tagged to\\nTagged Sales Staff Name Staff name (as reflected in source) of staff customer tagged to in English \\n\\nTagged Sales Staff Supervisor Name Supervisor name  (as reflected in user access matrix -staff \\nhierarcy/relationship  ) of staff customer tagged to in English text\\n\\nTagged Sales Staff Supervisor Staff ID Supervisor staff ID (as reflected in user access matrix -staff \\nhierarcy/relationship  ) of staff customer tagged to\\n\\nTagged Sales Staff Region Region or Zone (as reflected in user access matrix -staff \\nhierarcy/relationship  ) of staff customer tagged to \\n\\nConfidential to CIMB and Intellect                                                                                                                                         Page 35\\n\\n\\n\\n4.9.3 AL003 – Product Risk vs. Customer Risk\\n\\nReport Name Alerts Report - Product Risk vs. Customer Risk\\nReport Purpose This report captures the Product Risk vs. Customer Risk (mismatch) alerts that \\n\\nhas been triggered on PMS. User will be able to see the list of customers of \\nwhich this alert has been triggered on based on the report selection criteria\\n\\nReport Selection Criteria \\n(This will appear as input fields\\nfor generating the report)\\n\\n Alert Date (Period)\\nClient (searchable field by name, ID or CIF)\\nCustomer Segment\\nSales Staff (this is for supervisor only and all the sales staff who reports the \\n\\nlogged in user will display in the drop-down field)\\nReport Sorting Sequence By default, records are grouped and sorted by sales staff name (ascending), \\n\\nCustomer name (ascending), date (ascending)\\nReport Page Break 50\\nDistribution Report can be exported in excel format\\nReport Frequency Ad hoc (as and when downloaded)\\nReport Ad Hoc Request Yes\\nReport Format Excel\\nCountry / Entity MY,SG, TH\\nAccess Access to report subject to user access matrix\\nRemarks Date Stamp (of as at when report is downloaded) should be stated\\n\\nField Description...","query":"customer risk rating product risk rating","norm_score":0.9632484978649919,"relevance_score":0.5307367935454899},{"filename":"PAD risk profile & asset allocation - TH.pdf","file_id":"file-V26J7FYijvFptYsJnQ28no","score":0.7523311887189258,"text":"Confidential to CIMB and Intellect                                                                                                                                                        Page 8\\n \\n\\n\\n\\n                                                                                                           \\n\\n3.2.12. At the time of defining the questions and option, user will get flag to mark the question as a single \\nresponse type or multiple response type. Based upon the flag the risk profile question will be rendered.\\nA sample of how the question will be rendered for single response questionnaire and multiple \\nresponse questionnaire is attached below.\\n\\nScreen 1.4.3\\n\\n \\n\\n3.2.13. There can be questions which may not be used for scoring, but only for information or deciding if \\ndependent question or set of questions needs to be answered. For all such questions, the weightage \\nfor the responses will be set to “0” to exclude these questions from risk profile score calculation.\\n\\n3.2.14. There would be provision for dependent questions which can be answered only if a given response \\nis selected from a previous question.\\n\\n3.2.15. The Risk Profile Questionnaire will have an effective start date and effective end date. A \\nquestionnaire defined in the system will remain active from effective start date to effective end date \\n(both days inclusive).\\n\\n3.2.16. Multiple Risk Profile Questionnaire can be maintained in the system for a unique combination of \\nCustomer Category, Questionnaire Type, Effective Start Date and Effective End Date.\\n\\n3.2.17. A separate maintenance will be provided for defining the Disclaimer notes that will be displayed at \\nthe end of risk profiling in RWS.\\n\\n3.2.18. Below is a sample excel file, highlighting the risk profile process and risk profile score calculation \\nlogic:\\n\\nBusiness Validation\\n Only one questionnaire for a combination Customer Category and Profile can remain active for a given \\n\\neffective start date and effective end date.\\n If on the day of risk profiling, there are no questionnaire active as per the effective start date and \\n\\neffective end date, i.e. for the given date there are no risk profile questionnaire maintained, the system\\nwould throw an error at the time of risk profiling.\\n\\nConfidential to CIMB and Intellect                                                                                                                                                        Page 9...","query":"Context: This is a follow-up question in a conversation. Please maintain context from the previous discussion.\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"these\\", \\"the above\\")\\n• If such references exist, identify what they refer to based on the conversation history\\n• Internally clarify the question to make it self-contained and explicit\\n\\nSTEP 2 - Focused Response Generation:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: what is the diffrence between CRR and PRRR requi