aire \\n\\t4.9.4.2.​View Questionnaire \\n\\t4.9.4.3.​Modify Questionnaire \\n\\t4.9.4.4.​Authorization \\n\\n\\t4.9.5.​Rendering the Questions in the Client Portal for Survey Response Capture \\n\\t4.9.5.1.​Surveys Display in Client Portal \\n\\t4.9.5.2.​Sorting Mechanism and Number of Surveys to be displayed to the Customer \\n\\t4.9.5.3.​Storing the Responses for Survey \\n\\n\\t4.9.6.​Display of Feedback Response Rate in Customer Dashboard in RM Office \\n\\n\\t4.10.​Reports \\n\\t4.10.1.​Gain/Loss Report \\n\\t4.10.1.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.1.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.1.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.2.​Grandfathering Report \\n\\t4.10.2.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.2.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.2.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.3.​Order Statement for Client \\n\\t4.10.3.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.3.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.3.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.4.​Consolidated Holding Report \\n\\t4.10.4.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.4.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.4.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.5.​Order Rejection Report \\n\\t4.10.5.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.5.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.5.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.6.​SIP Due Report \\n\\t4.10.6.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.6.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.6.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.7.​Corporate Action Report for Client \\n\\t4.10.7.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.7.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.7.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.8.​SIP/SWP/STP For Client \\n\\t4.10.8.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.8.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.8.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.9.​Holding Report for Client \\n\\t4.10.9.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.9.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.9.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.10.​ELSS Report \\n\\t4.10.10.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.10.2.​Field Level Details \\n\\t4.10.10.3.​Report Sample \\n\\n\\t4.10.11.​One Pager Report \\n\\t4.10.11.1.​Purpose \\n\\t4.10.11.3.​Report Sample...","query":"[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: What reports are generated for clients? requirements rules conditions","norm_score":0.9720521237577221,"relevance_score":0.6829253779397977},{"filename":"PAD PMS Reports & Statements_Final [v1] (1).pdf","file_id":"file-VSdCdTX8SHy7CqgC9g3GRL","score":0.7996165433061174,"text":"Confidential to CIMB and Intellect                                                                                                                                         Page 4\\n\\n\\n\\nProcess <Reports & Statements>\\n\\n1. Process Objective\\n\\nThis  document  describes  in  detail  each  and  every  MIS  reports  and  Holdings  Statements  that  is  being\\ngenerated in RWS from Portfolio Management System.\\n\\n2. Process flow Map\\n\\nProcess Area Process Sub Process Intellect Module Intellect Process Name\\n\\nReports &\\nStatements\\n\\nReports &\\nStatements\\n\\nPMS Portfolio Management\\nSystem\\n\\n3. Process flow diagram\\n\\nNone\\n\\n4. Description of process steps\\n\\nFor each of the Report that system generates, this document describes the input criteria, the purpose that reports \\nserves, and the stakeholders for which the report has been generated. Each of the report also discusses for which \\ncountry that specific report is applicable.\\n\\n4.1. PMS_01 Risk Profile:\\n\\nReport Name Risk Profile \\n\\nReport Purpose This report captures customers’ Risk Profile records. User will be able to see the list of \\ncustomers who have completed the risk profile questionnaire along with their risk \\nprofile results based on the date range and other filter criteria selected. Users will be \\nable to study the number of times sales staff conduct risk profile for all customers. \\n\\nReport Selection Criteria\\n(This will appear as input\\nfields for generating the\\n\\nreport)\\n\\nDate Range (Current RPQ Date)\\nClient (searchable field by name, ID)\\nCustomer Type (Individual/Corporate)\\nCustomer Segment\\nSales Staff (this is for supervisor only and all the sales staff who reports the logged in \\nuser will display in the drop-down field)\\nRegion/Zone (drop down)\\nBranch (drop down)\\n\\nReport Sorting Sequence By default, records are grouped and sorted by current RPQ Date (descending), \\ncustomer name(ascending), sales staff name (ascending)\\n\\nReport Page Break 50 (for screen report - preview before downloading report)\\nDistribution Report must be able to be downloaded and save in compatible MS Excel format\\n\\nReport Frequency Ad hoc (as and when downloaded)\\nReport Ad Hoc Request Yes\\n\\nConfidential to CIMB and Intellect                                                                                                                                         Page 5\\n\\n\\n\\nReport Format Excel\\nCountry / Entity MY,SG,TH\\n\\nAccess Access to report subject to user access matrix\\nRemarks  Date Range search will use the current RPQ creation/update date;\\n\\nDate Stamp (of as...","query":"[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: What reports are generated for clients? process workflow steps","norm_score":0.9052569540668461,"relevance_score":0.6200715732323296},{"filename":"TH Feedback PAD Reports_V3.pdf","file_id":"file-PUMAG4JdCF54QPNfrzVaab","score":0.8040970842511991,"text":"Lead – Break by Branch..................................................................................................................6\\n3. Lead Tracking – Detail....................................................................................................................7\\n4. Lead Tracking – by RM...................................................................................................................8\\n5. Campaign Monitoring....................................................................................................................9\\n6. Lead Monitoring...........................................................................................................................12\\n7. Campaign Details..........................................................................................................................14\\n8. Offsite Branch Service..................................................................................................................16\\n9. Offsite by RM................................................................................................................................17\\n10. Client Onboarding....................................................................................................................18\\n11. SMS Report..............................................................................................................................20\\n12. Assignment Tracking................................................................................................................21\\n13. Assignment History..................................................................................................................22\\n14. Service Request Monitoring....................................................................................................23\\n15. List of Call Report.....................................................................................................................24\\n\\n\\n\\n4\\n\\nIntroduction\\n\\n The purpose of the PAD is to expand upon the reports applicable for CIMB Thailand Implementation. Following are \\nthe reports that are applicable:\\n\\n Lead Tracking – Overall\\n Lead – Break by Branch\\n Lead Tracking – Detail\\n Lead Tracking – by RM\\n Offsite Branch Service\\n Offsite by RM\\n Campaign Monitoring\\n Lead Monitoring\\n Campaign Detail\\n Client Onboarding\\n SMS Report\\n Assignment Tracking\\n Assignment History\\n Service Request Monitoring\\n List of Call Report\\n\\nThe access to the reports work...","query":"[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: What reports are generated for clients?","norm_score":0.9183353642267088,"relevance_score":0.5996534081325562},{"filename":"UJ_3.4.3_Customer Response.docx.pdf","file_id":"file-8RxfKwnrRfsWttfnAmKavF","score":0.6269812913240213,"text":"UJ_3.4.3_Customer Response.docx\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\nUser Journey Document \\n\\n \\n \\n\\n \\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n \\n\\nConfidential to Customer and Intellect Page 1 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\nCONTENTS \\nUSER JOURNEY_3.4.3 – CUSTOMER RESPONSE 3 \\n\\n \\n\\n●  \\n\\nConfidential to Customer and Intellect Page 2 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\nUser Journey_3.4.3 – Customer Response \\n\\n1. Process Objective –  \\nThe objective of this process is to capture investor’s responses for a voluntary corporate action (i.e. for \\na Corporate Action which requires Customer Response Capture, it could Corporate Action like Voting \\nRights or Conversion). \\n \\n \\n\\n2. Event Definition Process flow Map \\n \\n \\n\\nProcess \\nArea \\n\\nProcess Sub Process Intellect Module Intellect Process Name \\n\\nCorporate \\nActions \\n\\nCustomer \\nResponse \\n\\n \\nIntellect Portfolio \\n\\nManagement \\nExchange \\n\\nCorporate Action –Customer \\nResponse - \\n\\n \\n \\n \\n\\n \\n \\n\\n3. Description of process steps –  \\n\\nProcess Description \\n● This process is applicable only for voluntary corporate actions. Customer response is \\n\\nentered after entitlement calculation on record date.  \\n● The process will need to be completed on or before the customer response date.  \\n● In case of corporate action like Voting Rights, user will have provision to capture the \\n\\nresolutions and customer response for each resolution.  \\n \\n\\nConfidential to Customer and Intellect Page 3 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\n● User can capture the customer response at individual record level and save it. Once \\nresponse for all the customers is captured user can submit the same \\n\\n● The settlement process will depend on the customer response \\n● Customer details and the CA specific details are populated automatically in the customer \\n\\nresponse window. \\n● The user can Modify the Customer response if required \\n● The saved record moves to Checker''s grid for Authorization \\n● The Checker has a provision to view the Event details and the Customer level benefits , \\n\\nreview it and Authorize or Reject  in case of any discrepancies \\n● If rejected, the record moves to the maker for modification and re processing \\n● Authorized customer response records moves for Settlement Process. \\n● Application would fetch all investors who have holdings in the security and for whom \\n\\nresponse needs to be captured. \\n\\n. \\n\\n \\n4. Input details – Displayed \\n\\n \\n5. Validations \\n\\n● The event should be a voluntary corporate action. \\n● Entitlement calculation should have been authorized. \\n\\n \\n\\nException Management \\n● Mandatory Field Verification \\n\\n●.i.2.●.i. System will valid...","query":"[focused response directive] please","norm_score":0.4013457832624565,"relevance_score":0.4534397330754554},{"filename":"WQ-Observation Solutioning_V1.0_SBI_CCV1.6.docx.pdf","file_id":"file-DApMRsCEwmyK4e4XhZnwY9","score":0.48948398140159083,"text":"7. User will not be allowed to resubmit the order. He/She has to start from the transact screen again. \\n\\n \\n\\nNo retrigger for the following Error codes \\nError Code Error Description \\n\\n0110 ACCOUNT CLOSED \\n0112 ACCOUNT IS LOCKED - PLS. TRY AGAIN \\n0113 ACCOUNT STOPPED \\n2817 CANNOT PROCESS THE ACCOUNT-INOPERATIVE \\n0398 INSUFFICIENT FUNDS \\n \\n\\n8. If the “Fund Transfer API” has failed due to a technical reason, the status of the order will be updated as “In \\n\\nProgress”.  The following error codes will be considered as technical reasons. \\n\\nRe-triggered for the following Error codes (Technical reasons) \\nError Code Error Description \\n\\nInternal to SBI and Intellect  Page 67 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n                                                                                                                                                                                          \\n\\n6970 DP NOT AVAILABLE. ACCT CANNOT BE OVERDRAWN \\nSI001 EXCEPTION WHILE PROCESSING THE RESPONSE \\nSI002 ERROR IN CONNECTING DESTINATION SERVER \\n0155 PL CONTACT SERVICE DESK     INVM   X04T  \\n2066 SWEEP DETAILS NOT FOUND \\nSI014 TIMEOUT PLEASE TRY AFTER SOMETIME \\nSI011  INPUT STRING/REQUEST WAS NOT IN CORRECT FORMAT \\n0545 APPLICATION NOT ACTIVE. \\n7527 CIF not scrutinized by LCPC \\n\\n8123 \\nWITHDRAWAL/TRANSFER STOPPED KYC UPDATION OVERDUE IN \\nACCOUNT \\n\\nSI094  INVALID REQUEST REFERENCE NUMBER \\nSI163 JOURNAL/REFERENCE NUMBER MISMATCH \\nSI007 Unable to process due to technical error \\n \\n\\n9. On success, the order will be then sent to RTA through RTA API and the status of the order will be updated as \\n\\n“Settlement Pending” in order book. \\n\\n10. If “RTA API” fails, then the order will remain in “Settlement Pending” state. \\n\\n11. The status of the order can be accessed from Order Book. \\n\\n12. On every 30 mins, system will again execute all the orders that are currently in “In Progress” state till the \\n\\ncut-off time. \\n\\n13. At the time of execution, system will first call the “Fund Transfer Enquiry API” to check if the amount has been \\n\\ndebited from the customer’s account. \\n\\n14. If the response from “Fund Transfer Enquiry API” is “Success”, (Response Status “0”) and the amount has been \\n\\ndebited from customer’s investment account (Journal_number provided in the response), system will call the \\n\\n“RTA API” and the status will be updated as “Settlement pending”. \\n\\n15. If the amount has not been debited from the customer’s account (Journal_number is null in the response), \\n\\nthen the Fund Transfer API will be called again \\n\\n16. If th...","query":"[focused response directive] please","norm_score":0,"relevance_score":0.20311729564894093}]', '{"domain":"wealth_management","vectorstore_id":"vs_689b49252a4c8191a12a1528a475fbd8","response_id":"8a77014a-7765-4f13-8768-4554a535ecbb","is_conversational":false,"mode":"concise","processing_time_seconds":92.93,"request_id":"10b4a5ff-ac6a-4c24-91e6-f8c7b2890ef8"}', '2025-10-31 06:40:12.255813'),
('43', '16', 'user', 'How does the order placement workflow work?', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-10-31 06:41:15.81386'),
('44', '16', 'assistant', '# **KG + VectorStore Answer - [Focused Response Directive]\n\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\n\nUser''s Question: How does the order placement workflow work?**\n\n_Generated: 2025-10-31 06:41_\n\n## **Answer**\n\n**Direct Answer:**  \n- A dealer places a single or aggregated order in blotter or the normal order window. <sup><a href="#cite-2">[2]</a></sup> [KG:dataentity:order]  \n- The order moves through two stages: placement and execution, with possible aggregation. <sup><a href="#cite-2">[2]</a></sup> [KG:dataentity:order]  \n- The blotter maintains three queues: Placed, Pending for Execution, Executed. <sup><a href="#cite-2">[2]</a></sup> [KG:dataentity:order] <sup><a href="#cite-1">[1]</a></sup>\n\n**Key Points:**  \n• Point 1: Entry can be blotter or standard window; aggregation is allowed. <sup><a href="#cite-2">[2]</a></sup> [KG:dataentity:order]  \n• Point 2: Two-stage flow: placement, then execution; aggregation helps cost efficiency. <sup><a href="#cite-2">[2]</a></sup> [KG:dataentity:order]  \n• Point 3: Compliance checks, validations, cut-off timing, charges, settlement details, and documents are part of the workflow. <sup><a href="#cite-1">[1]</a></sup> [KG:compliance:validations]\n\n**Note:** This reflects the general order placement flow; specifics vary by security type and client. <sup><a href="#cite-2">[2]</a></sup>\n\n---\n\n## **Citations**\n\n<a id="cite-1"></a>\n**[1]** → **UJ_2.1_Order placement.docx.pdf**\n\n<a id="cite-2"></a>\n**[2]** → **UJ_2.3_Place an order.docx.pdf**\n\n<a id="cite-3"></a>\n**[3]** → **OMS_ProductFitment_Doc_UNB_Ver1.4.docx.pdf**\n\n\n---\n\n## **Sources by File**\n\n- **OMS_ProductFitment_Doc_UNB_Ver1.4.docx.pdf** → [3]\n- **UJ_2.1_Order placement.docx.pdf** → [1]\n- **UJ_2.3_Place an order.docx.pdf** → [2]\n', '3d6833a0-7896-4491-b53d-05932d9279c6', '[{"filename":"UJ_2.1_Order placement.docx.pdf","file_id":"file-NdswJAJAwJtTUv8LK3g3SB","score":0.7813604100269788,"text":"● Charges Details: Fees and charges defined in the FnC module are populated in charges details \\nsection. In the end, it provides total amount of charges and settlement amount \\n\\n● Settlement Details: This section consists of information needed for successful settlement of an \\norder. E.g. Fx currency rate, counterparty details, settlement date  \\n\\n● Other Details:  This section allows the user to enter remark, if any, before placing an order. \\n● Document Upload: A user may need to upload mandatory documents to place an order. This \\n\\nupload is done through document upload at the bottom of the screen. \\n● Scrutiny Check List: Depending on a client, security and order type, verification is performed in \\n\\nthe scrutiny checklist section. \\n● Deviations: While placing an order, there would be error or exception based on given information. \\n\\nThese deviations are shown in the deviations section in order placement screen.  \\n \\n \\n\\nBelow are the mandatory fields. \\n\\nField  Name   Data Type \\n\\nMandatory \\n/Non-Mandat\\n\\nory \\n/Conditional \\nMandatory Description Input Type \\n\\nExecution Character Mandatory \\nIt describes whether order is Execution or \\nAdvisory User selection \\n\\nMode of Instruction Character Mandatory \\n\\nDescribes the communication mode used \\nby the client for order capture \\nWritten - Fax, Written - Copy, Email, \\nTelephone User selection \\n\\nCustomer NO \\nAlpha \\nNumeric Mandatory \\n\\nUniquely mapped to base, to place an \\norder for an individual User selection \\n\\nPortfolio \\nAlpha \\nNumeric Mandatory Used to select portfolio of a customer User selection \\n\\nAsset \\nAlpha \\nNumeric Mandatory Name of an asset User selection \\n\\nSecurity Code Name \\nAlpha \\nNumeric Mandatory \\n\\nName of security code mapped to a \\nsecurity User selection \\n\\nMarket \\nAlpha \\nNumeric Mandatory \\n\\nName of the market where order is being \\nplaced User selection \\n\\nOrder Type \\nAlpha \\nNumeric Mandatory Type of order e.g. Buy, sell, etc. User selection \\n\\nSecurity Account \\nAlpha \\nNumeric Mandatory Security account to be debited/credited User selection \\n\\nCash Settlement \\nAccount \\n\\nAlpha \\nNumeric Mandatory \\n\\nShows cash settlement account for a \\ntransaction User selection \\n\\nSource/Transfer Out \\nclosing id \\n\\nAlpha \\nNumeric Mandatory \\n\\nId to identify the multiple tranches in \\nsubscription of a fund User selection \\n\\nOrder Final Status Character Mandatory Order final status i.e. clean or discrepant Display \\n\\nConfidential to Customer and Intellect Page 4 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\nField  Name   Data Type \\n\\nMandatory \\n/Non-Mandat\\n\\nory \\n/Condit...","query":"[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: How does the order placement workflow work? requirements rules conditions","norm_score":1,"relevance_score":0.569805546544597},{"filename":"UJ_2.3_Place an order.docx.pdf","file_id":"file-R8dsXNt9kYhUhqCwyaDrpt","score":0.7565573180499325,"text":"UJ_2.3_Place an order.docx\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\nUser Journey Document \\n\\n \\n \\n\\n \\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n \\n\\nConfidential to Customer and Intellect Page 1 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\nCONTENTS \\nUSER JOURNEY_2.3 – PLACE AN ORDER 3 \\n\\n \\n\\n●  \\n\\nConfidential to Customer and Intellect Page 2 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\nUser Journey_2.3 – Place an Order \\n\\n1. Process Objective –  \\nThe objective of this process is to place an order by a dealer. Authorized order(s) (single or aggregated), \\nbased on the security type would be either sent to blotter or normal order window. \\n\\n \\n2. Customer to wealth Process flow Map \\n\\n \\n \\n\\nProcess Area Process Sub Process Intellect Module Intellect Process \\nName \\n\\nBlotter Order \\nPlacement \\n\\n \\nOMS Blotter – Order \\n\\nPlacement \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n \\n\\n3. Description of process steps –  \\n\\nProcess Description \\n\\nBlotter consists of three queues i.e. Placed, Pending for execution and Executed. In the \\nExecuted queue, multiple trades can be aggregated to simplify the process of contracting and \\nsettlement. Each swift sent has cost associated with it. Hence aggregation of trades before \\nsettlement could reduce cost for the business and can improve efficiency.  \\n\\n \\n● The process of order placement mainly differs based on the type of security and \\n\\nwhether a security is processed through Blotter. In Blotter dealer can select a \\ncounterparty to place a transaction.   \\n\\n● Blotter transactions pass through two stage i.e. order placement and order \\nexecution. In the case of order placement, dealer places order with a counterparty.  \\n\\n● Based on the aggregation parameters like order type, security type, ISIN, transaction \\n\\nConfidential to Customer and Intellect Page 3 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\ntype orders can be aggregated for placement with a counterparty. \\n● The dealer can place a single order or an aggregated order. \\n● Eventually, whether aggregated or single, an order is placed by clicking on place \\n\\nbutton in Blotter.  \\n● When any willing counterparty shows interest to buy/sell at desired price, dealer \\n\\nexecutes that order. (This is outside the system). However, execution details can be \\nentered by Dealer which is covered by the  UJ_2.4_Execute an Order \\n\\n● Orders that are not processed through blotter –  \\n1. For Mutual Funds, Buy or Sell order is directly sent to fund house and fund \\n\\nhouse executes the transaction.  \\n2. When the user clicks on Place/Execute, order related to Alternatives is \\n\\nplaced and directly sent for settlement. \\n \\n\\nBelow are the mandatory fields. \\n\\nField  Name   Data Typ...","query":"[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: How does the order placement workflow work? process workflow steps","norm_score":0.054189817133600285,"relevance_score":0.33897913497910265},{"filename":"OMS_ProductFitment_Doc_UNB_Ver1.4.docx.pdf","file_id":"file-ER4Vq5EKXkkvbhiNtP8ZTa","score":0.7551362347893246,"text":"iv. Business Rules: \\na) Subscription orders can only be placed if investor has adequate cash balance in \\n\\nhis/her cash account. \\nb) In case of change in FX Rate or Fee, SMS will be sent to Head of RM. Ops needs to \\n\\nvalidate if approval has been obtained and approval document needs to be \\nuploaded in the system. \\n\\nv. Actor / Entitlements: \\na) Relationship Manager \\nb) Branch Teller \\n\\nvi. Trigger: Manual \\nvii. Output Details: Orders, Trades, Position \\n\\nviii. Alerts: Alert to be generated in case there is a change in FX Rate, Fee Override \\nix. Notification: None \\n\\n \\n5. Next Process – None \\n\\n \\n6. Process Gaps -  \\n\\ni. Lien to be marked with a Buffer for unit based orders \\n \\n \\n\\n7.  \\n\\n15 | Page \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n                                                                                                                                \\n\\nProcess ID_1.2 – Order Flow – Equity / FI / ETF / SP \\n\\n \\n1. Process Objective – The objective of this process is to capture orders, place, execute, confirm and settle. The \\n\\norder flow being discussed is only for Equity, Bonds, ETF and Structured Products. \\n \\n\\n2. Process Flow to Module Mapping:  \\n\\nProcess Area Process Sub Process Intellect Module Intellect Process Name \\n\\nOrder \\nManagement \\nSystem Order Flow   OMS Order Management \\n\\n \\n3. Process Flow Diagram: \\n\\n \\n\\n \\n\\n \\nProcess ID_1.2a – Order Initiation \\n\\n \\n\\n16 | Page \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n                                                                                                                                \\n\\n \\n\\n \\nProcess ID_1.2b – Order Routing \\n\\n4. Description of process steps –  \\na. Process Description: \\n\\ni. Orders for Fixed Income/Equity/ETF/Structured Product instrument can be initiated by \\nRelationship Manager, ISD, AMD or Treasury. \\n\\nii. The investment request may come through mail, fax or call from investor. In case of DPM \\ncustomers and Proprietary Funds, AMD will initiate the orders. \\n\\niii. For NDPMS portfolios, system will check for Communication Indemnity document in case \\nMode of Instruction is Mail, Fax or Telephone. \\n\\niv. During Order capture process, the document submission status and document expiry date will \\nbe validated by OMS. List of Documents for FI/Equity is as follows: \\nDocument Expiry Date Validation: \\nW8 Ben \\nFATCA \\nLeverage \\nPassport \\nEmirates ID \\nPOA \\n \\nDocument Submission Status: \\nLeverage Agreement - Leverage Orders \\nRisk Profile Document \\n\\n17 | Page...","query":"[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: How does the order placement workflow work? process workflow steps","norm_score":0,"relevance_score":0.32916038579596885}]', '{"domain":"wealth_management","vectorstore_id":"vs_689b49252a4c8191a12a1528a475fbd8","response_id":"3d6833a0-7896-4491-b53d-05932d9279c6","is_conversational":false,"mode":"concise","processing_time_seconds":48.61,"request_id":"3ce356df-7996-44a7-acb2-311463825d96"}', '2025-10-31 06:41:15.855631'),
('156', '66', 'assistant', 'In wealth management, **CRR** and **PRR** are standard risk measures used together to ensure investment suitability.\n\n---\n\n## 1. CRR – Customer Risk Rating\n\n**What it is:**  \nCRR (Customer Risk Rating) is the client’s overall **risk profile** – how much risk they are both willing and able to take.\n\n**How it’s determined:**\n\n- Based on a **risk profiling questionnaire** covering:\n  - Financial situation (income, assets, liabilities)\n  - Investment objectives (growth, income, capital preservation)\n  - Time horizon\n  - Experience and knowledge\n  - Attitude toward losses and volatility\n- The answers are scored and mapped to a **risk category**, e.g.:\n  - Very Conservative / Conservative\n  - Moderate / Balanced\n  - Aggressive / Very Aggressive  \n  (often also represented by numbers, like 1–5 or 1–6)\n- The CRR is:\n  - Stored in the system\n  - Valid only for a defined period (e.g., 1–2 years), after which the client must be re-profiled\n  - Mandatory before giving investment advice or placing new investment orders\n\nCRR expresses the **maximum risk level appropriate for that client**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. PRR – Product Risk Rating\n\n**What it is:**  \nPRR (Product Risk Rating) is the **risk level of an investment product**, such as a mutual fund, bond, equity, or model portfolio.\n\n**How it’s determined:**\n\n- Assigned by the firm’s **research/risk team** (and aligned with regulatory or external guidelines where applicable)\n- Uses a similar **scale as CRR** (e.g., 1–6, from low to high risk) so they can be directly compared\n- Based on product characteristics, such as:\n  - Asset class (equity vs. debt vs. cash)\n  - Volatility and historical drawdowns\n  - Credit quality and duration (for debt)\n  - Complexity, leverage, derivatives\n  - Liquidity and concentration risks\n\nExamples:\n- Government bond fund → low PRR (e.g., 1–2)\n- Balanced fund → medium PRR (e.g., 3–4)\n- Small-cap or sector equity fund → high PRR (e.g., 5–6)\n\nEvery product in the platform has a defined PRR.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How CRR and PRR Work Together\n\n### a) Suitability checks (CRR–PRR matching)\n\nBefore an order is placed, the system compares **client CRR vs. product PRR**:\n\n- **PRR ≤ CRR** → Generally suitable; order allowed.\n- **PRR slightly above CRR (e.g., +1 level)** →  \n  - System shows a **warning**.\n  - Client/advisor must **acknowledge** and confirm they still wish to proceed.\n- **PRR moderately above CRR (e.g., +2 levels)** →  \n  - Warning shown.\n  - Order typically routed for **supervisory / compliance approval** before execution.\n- **PRR far above CRR (e.g., >+2 levels)** →  \n  - **Hard stop**: order blocked as not suitable.\n\nThis creates an automated control to prevent mis-selling high-risk products to low-risk clients and to document any exceptions.\n\n---\n\n### b) Client onboarding and periodic review\n\n- During onboarding, the client completes the **risk questionnaire** → CRR is set.\n- If CRR is **missing or expired**, new investments are usually **not allowed** until the profile is updated.\n- Periodic re-profiling ensures CRR reflects current circumstances (e.g., income changes, life events).\n\n---\n\n### c) Portfolio construction and model portfolios\n\n- Firms define **model portfolios** for each risk level (e.g., Conservative, Moderate, Aggressive), each with a target asset allocation.\n- Once CRR is known:\n  - The system recommends the **model portfolio** corresponding to that CRR.\n  - Advisors use it as a baseline and then select specific products whose **PRRs fit within the client’s CRR**.\n- The overall portfolio risk (aggregate of product PRRs) is monitored to stay broadly consistent with the client’s CRR.\n\n---\n\n### d) Ongoing monitoring and reporting\n\n- Systems track whether a client’s **actual holdings** remain aligned with their CRR.\n- Reports and dashboards show:\n  - Portfolios that have drifted into higher risk than the CRR.\n  - All transactions where PRR > CRR and approvals/warnings were used.\n- Compliance and risk teams review these logs for **audit and regulatory reporting**.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Governance and Compliance\n\n- Regulators require:\n  - **Assessment of client risk appetite** (CRR).\n  - **Suitability of products** sold (via PRR and CRR–PRR matching).\n- Internal policies typically specify:\n  - Standardized **questionnaire** and scoring for CRR.\n  - No or limited manual override of CRR at profiling stage.\n  - Clear **approval workflows** for CRR–PRR mismatches.\n  - Regular review and governance of **product PRRs**.\n  - Mandatory **re-profiling** frequency and handling of expired CRRs.\n\nUsing CRR and PRR in this structured way provides a clear, auditable framework linking each client’s risk appetite to the risk of the products they hold.', 'resp_0bb65e492df7276700693db03cc1108191befacde2329fbdf0', NULL, '{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"fallback","confidence":0,"matchedKeywords":[]},"jobId":"job_1765650495019_lu9deb5du","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_0bb65e492df7276700693db03cc1108191befacde2329fbdf0"}', '2025-12-13 18:28:14.606357'),
