ion Process flow Map \\n \\n \\n\\nProcess \\nArea \\n\\nProcess Sub Process Intellect Module Intellect Process Name \\n\\nCorporate \\nActions \\n\\nCustomer \\nResponse \\n\\n \\nIntellect Portfolio \\n\\nManagement \\nExchange \\n\\nCorporate Action –Customer \\nResponse - \\n\\n \\n \\n \\n\\n \\n \\n\\n3. Description of process steps –  \\n\\nProcess Description \\n● This process is applicable only for voluntary corporate actions. Customer response is \\n\\nentered after entitlement calculation on record date.  \\n● The process will need to be completed on or before the customer response date.  \\n● In case of corporate action like Voting Rights, user will have provision to capture the \\n\\nresolutions and customer response for each resolution.  \\n \\n\\nConfidential to Customer and Intellect Page 3 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n       \\n\\n● User can capture the customer response at individual record level and save it. Once \\nresponse for all the customers is captured user can submit the same \\n\\n● The settlement process will depend on the customer response \\n● Customer details and the CA specific details are populated automatically in the customer \\n\\nresponse window. \\n● The user can Modify the Customer response if required \\n● The saved record moves to Checker''s grid for Authorization \\n● The Checker has a provision to view the Event details and the Customer level benefits , \\n\\nreview it and Authorize or Reject  in case of any discrepancies \\n● If rejected, the record moves to the maker for modification and re processing \\n● Authorized customer response records moves for Settlement Process. \\n● Application would fetch all investors who have holdings in the security and for whom \\n\\nresponse needs to be captured. \\n\\n. \\n\\n \\n4. Input details – Displayed \\n\\n \\n5. Validations \\n\\n● The event should be a voluntary corporate action. \\n● Entitlement calculation should have been authorized. \\n\\n \\n\\nException Management \\n● Mandatory Field Verification \\n\\n●.i.2.●.i. System will valid...","query":"[focused response directive] please","norm_score":0.3777210323142156,"relevance_score":0.4276249385910771},{"filename":"WQ-Observation Solutioning_V1.0_SBI_CCV1.6.docx.pdf","file_id":"file-DApMRsCEwmyK4e4XhZnwY9","score":0.48948398140159083,"text":"7. User will not be allowed to resubmit the order. He/She has to start from the transact screen again. \\n\\n \\n\\nNo retrigger for the following Error codes \\nError Code Error Description \\n\\n0110 ACCOUNT CLOSED \\n0112 ACCOUNT IS LOCKED - PLS. TRY AGAIN \\n0113 ACCOUNT STOPPED \\n2817 CANNOT PROCESS THE ACCOUNT-INOPERATIVE \\n0398 INSUFFICIENT FUNDS \\n \\n\\n8. If the “Fund Transfer API” has failed due to a technical reason, the status of the order will be updated as “In \\n\\nProgress”.  The following error codes will be considered as technical reasons. \\n\\nRe-triggered for the following Error codes (Technical reasons) \\nError Code Error Description \\n\\nInternal to SBI and Intellect  Page 67 \\n \\n\\n\\n\\n                                                                                                                                                                                          \\n\\n6970 DP NOT AVAILABLE. ACCT CANNOT BE OVERDRAWN \\nSI001 EXCEPTION WHILE PROCESSING THE RESPONSE \\nSI002 ERROR IN CONNECTING DESTINATION SERVER \\n0155 PL CONTACT SERVICE DESK     INVM   X04T  \\n2066 SWEEP DETAILS NOT FOUND \\nSI014 TIMEOUT PLEASE TRY AFTER SOMETIME \\nSI011  INPUT STRING/REQUEST WAS NOT IN CORRECT FORMAT \\n0545 APPLICATION NOT ACTIVE. \\n7527 CIF not scrutinized by LCPC \\n\\n8123 \\nWITHDRAWAL/TRANSFER STOPPED KYC UPDATION OVERDUE IN \\nACCOUNT \\n\\nSI094  INVALID REQUEST REFERENCE NUMBER \\nSI163 JOURNAL/REFERENCE NUMBER MISMATCH \\nSI007 Unable to process due to technical error \\n \\n\\n9. On success, the order will be then sent to RTA through RTA API and the status of the order will be updated as \\n\\n“Settlement Pending” in order book. \\n\\n10. If “RTA API” fails, then the order will remain in “Settlement Pending” state. \\n\\n11. The status of the order can be accessed from Order Book. \\n\\n12. On every 30 mins, system will again execute all the orders that are currently in “In Progress” state till the \\n\\ncut-off time. \\n\\n13. At the time of execution, system will first call the “Fund Transfer Enquiry API” to check if the amount has been \\n\\ndebited from the customer’s account. \\n\\n14. If the response from “Fund Transfer Enquiry API” is “Success”, (Response Status “0”) and the amount has been \\n\\ndebited from customer’s investment account (Journal_number provided in the response), system will call the \\n\\n“RTA API” and the status will be updated as “Settlement pending”. \\n\\n15. If the amount has not been debited from the customer’s account (Journal_number is null in the response), \\n\\nthen the Fund Transfer API will be called again \\n\\n16. If th...","query":"[focused response directive] please","norm_score":0,"relevance_score":0.2924803153157261}]', '{"domain":"wealth_management","vectorstore_id":"vs_689b49252a4c8191a12a1528a475fbd8","response_id":"dbb9ae7d-c05b-4a25-8eac-1036472e525b","is_conversational":false,"mode":"concise","processing_time_seconds":78.37,"request_id":"698d0333-7333-4398-be56-c2f6de11a4ba"}', '2025-11-07 04:31:39.124228'),
('158', '67', 'assistant', '### How portfolio rebalancing is done in the application\n\n#### 1. Define rebalancing tolerance at model level\n\nDuring model portfolio creation/maintenance, the user configures a **tolerance** field for the model. This tolerance explicitly controls when rebalancing should occur: \n- The model setup includes a `Tolerance` parameter with the remark: *“Basis tolerance defined rebalancing will be done”* .\n- Asset allocation (target weights per asset class/security) is also defined as part of the model, along with risk profile, time horizon, and other attributes .\n\nIn effect, the rebalancing logic uses this stored tolerance and the target allocations to detect when the live portfolio has drifted enough to justify a rebalance.\n\n#### 2. Identify rebalancing need and create a model order\n\nWhen the system or user determines that a client’s portfolio has drifted beyond the defined tolerance for a subscribed model, a **model order** of type **Rebalancing** is initiated:\n- Transactions at model level explicitly support a `Rebalancing` transaction type alongside Purchase, Redemption, and Switch .\n- A unique **Model Order** is created with a system‑generated **Unique ID** (model order unique number). This ID acts as the umbrella identifier under which all underlying security‑level orders for that rebalance are grouped .\n- The **Model Investment Amount** (the total amount for the model after rebalance) is captured at model order level (e.g., `orderamt` in the model order initiation), from which security‑wise amounts are derived based on target allocations .\n\n#### 3. Construct the rebalancing basket (underlying MF orders)\n\nBased on the current holdings versus target allocation and the model’s tolerance setting, the system builds the **rebalancing basket**:\n- For each mutual fund/security in the model, the system compares current actual weights to target weights and calculates buy/sell quantities required to move back within tolerance.\n- The resulting actions are represented as underlying orders under the model order:\n  - For pure buy/sell at fund level, underlying orders appear as **Purchase** or **Redemption** for the respective mutual fund .\n  - For changes between funds, the system can represent it as a **Switch (Rebalancing)**, where there is a **Switch Out Security Name** and **Switch In Security Name** specifically for rebalancing order types .\n- Each underlying MF order gets its own **Order ID**, but remains linked to the model’s **Unique ID** so that the rebalance is tracked as a single event at model level .\n\n#### 4. Submit, validate, and approve the rebalance\n\nOnce the rebalancing basket is prepared, the normal order lifecycle is used, applied to all underlying orders as part of the model order:\n- **Order capture & submission**: The rebalancing transaction (model order) is captured, with computed transaction amounts/units per mutual fund security .\n- **Validations**: Standard validations apply at this stage (e.g., product eligibility, risk profile checks, mandatory field checks), similar to regular mutual fund orders and model‑based orders. The system validates and generates the unique model order ID at this stage .\n- **Authorization/approval**: \n  - Submitted orders go for supervisor approval before execution, consistent with the standard mutual fund workflow .\n  - If any risk deviations or constraints exist, additional approval layers (e.g., higher‑level approvers) may be required, as per the same rule set used for standard MF transactions .\n\n#### 5. Trade execution and routing\n\nAfter approval, the system executes the rebalancing by routing all underlying orders to the product processor/RTA:\n- **Order routing**: Approved underlying orders (Purchase/Redemption/Switch) created under the Rebalancing model order are routed to the fund execution processor/RTA for fulfillment .\n- **Synchronous execution per model order**: All underlying orders under a given model order are expected to be sent together, and the **Order Date** is recorded at model level for the full rebalance set .\n- **Status tracking**: \n  - Model‑level status (e.g., Pending, In Progress, Expired, Failed) reflects the overall state of the rebalance .\n  - Each constituent order has its own **Order Status** (e.g., Pending, In Progress, Settlement Pending, Failed, Rejected, Settled), **Trade Date**, and amount, all visible for monitoring and exception handling .\n\n#### 6. Settlement and portfolio update\n\nWhen the RTA/trade file is received, the holdings are updated to reflect the completed rebalance:\n- **Settlement**: The system processes settlement files from the RTA/product processor and updates the customer’s mutual fund holdings accordingly, following the same settlement flow used for standard MF transactions .\n- **Portfolio realignment**: \n  - Post‑settlement, the client portfolio linked to the model reflects the new holdings and weights, now realigned closer to the model’s target allocation and within the specified tolerance.\n  - The model order’s final status is updated (e.g., Settled) once all underlying orders in the rebalancing basket are settled .\n\n#### 7. Monitoring and reporting\n\nThe rebalancing event and its underlying transactions are visible in the order monitoring and reporting views:\n- The **Order Book** can be searched and viewed by model name/ID, allowing users to see all orders placed within a model, including those with **Rebalancing** transaction type .\n- Model‑level fields like Model Name, Portfolio Name, Model Investment Amount, and Model Investment Status help track and audit each rebalance instance  .\n\nOverall, portfolio rebalancing in the application is executed as a **model order of type Rebalancing**, governed by the tolerance defined in model portfolio maintenance, decomposed into underlying mutual‑fund orders, processed through the standard MF order lifecycle (validation, approval, routing, settlement), and tracked end‑to‑end at both model and individual order level.\n\n---\n\n#### Sources\n\n- [1] JBR_Journey of Creating Model Portfolio_V1_CCV1.pdf\n- [2] JBR_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - G073 Part A and Part B - Basket based order trigger (1).pdf\n- [3] Maybank_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF_V12_CCV10_Part 1.pdf\n', '7e79fb71-de0f-407c-81da-62dc1ebf69fa', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["Model Portfolio Maintenance","G073 - Model based order trigger","Model Portfolio – Order Placement","CRISIL Portfolio Composition Master","Portfolio Master","MF Portfolio File (Crisil)","CRISIL master","Wealth Qube","HSBC PWS","Intellect"],"seed_node_ids":["datastore:model_pf_maintenance","report:model_pf_order_placement","report:g073_model_based_order_trigger","datastore:crisil_pf_composition_master","system:model_pf_maintenance","datastore:mf_pf_file_crisil","datastore:crisil_master","system:hsbc_pws","datastore:pf_master","system:crisil_master","system:intellect","system:wealth_qube","dataentity:scm_scheme_cd","dataentity:model_pf_maintenance"],"expanded_nodes":60,"expanded_edges":116,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: how is portfolio rebalancing is done in the application?","What is the end-to-end process for portfolio rebalancing within the application, including inputs, rules, triggers, calculations, validation, approvals, and trade execution?","Describe the portfolio rebalancing workflow in the application: data inputs (current holdings, target allocations, client risk profile), rebalancing triggers (scheduled, drift thresholds, advisor instruction), calculations (allocation drift, transaction costs, tax considerations, constraints), validation and compliance checks, user interfaces and screens to initiate/monitor/approve rebalances, and the trade execution path (order generation, brokerage/fill, settlement, and audit trails), along with reporting and post-rebalance updates.","[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: how is portfolio rebalancing is done in the application? Name","[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: how is portfolio rebalancing is done in the application? Mutual Funds","[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: how is portfolio rebalancing is done in t