('160', '68', 'assistant', 'Below is a cleaned-up, structured version of the raw answer. I’ve removed internal file links, kept the substance, and focused on the business flow, key data, systems, and controls.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Order Capture & Submission\n\nThe lifecycle starts when an investor (or relationship manager) places a mutual fund order.\n\n**Typical actions:**\n- Select client and investment account/folio.\n- Choose scheme (by name, ISIN, or scheme code).\n- Choose transaction type:\n  - Purchase (fresh or additional)\n  - Redemption\n  - Switch (from one scheme to another)\n  - Systematic plans (SIP, SWP, STP, etc.)\n- Enter amount or units.\n- For fresh folios, capture:\n  - Investor details (PAN, tax status, bank details, etc.)\n  - Nominee details (name, DOB, relationship, allocation %, guardian if minor).\n  - Or explicit “nomination not opted” declaration.\n\n**Key data elements:**\n- Customer ID, account/folio number.\n- Scheme code/ISIN, scheme name.\n- Transaction type (purchase/redemption/switch).\n- Amount or units.\n- Nominee details (for new folios).\n- Internal order ID.\n\nOrders may also originate from:\n- **Model portfolios / baskets**: a single model/basket order generates multiple underlying fund orders, all linked by a unique model/basket order ID.\n\nOrders are usually added to a **cart** for review and then submitted.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Order Validation & Prerequisites\n\nBefore the order moves forward, the system performs basic validations.\n\n**Core checks:**\n- All mandatory fields present and correctly formatted.\n- **KYC status**:\n  - Must be valid/approved; otherwise, hard stop.\n- **Client eligibility**:\n  - Certain tax statuses (e.g., some NRI categories) or regulatory flags may disallow MF transactions.\n- **Account setup**:\n  - Valid bank mandate/payment method for purchases.\n  - For fresh folios: PAN, bank details, nominee/opt-out, etc.\n\nIf any prerequisite fails, the order is rejected or returned to the user for correction and cannot proceed.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Compliance & Fund Eligibility Checks\n\nOnce basic validation passes, the system applies product and regulatory rules.\n\n**Fund & product checks:**\n- Scheme is open and eligible for the requested transaction type.\n- Scheme master data allows:\n  - Purchases/redemptions/switches as requested.\n  - No suspension or closure for that scheme/class.\n\n**Suitability & risk checks:**\n- Compare **fund risk rating** vs. **client risk profile**:\n  - If fund risk > client risk appetite:\n    - Warning (soft stop) and possible override/approval, or\n    - Hard stop, depending on policy.\n- If client risk profile is missing/expired:\n  - New purchases/switches are blocked until updated.\n\n**Amount/units checks:**\n- Minimum investment / minimum additional purchase.\n- Minimum redemption amount/units.\n- Redemption units ≤ available units in the client’s holdings.\n\n**Soft vs. hard stops:**\n- **Hard stops**: regulatory or critical rules (e.g., invalid KYC, exceeding holdings) – order cannot proceed.\n- **Soft stops**: policy-based warnings (e.g., mild risk mismatch) – may proceed with explicit consent and/or higher-level approval.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Order Routing & Execution\n\nAfter passing checks, the order enters the execution workflow.\n\n**Internal authorization (maker-checker):**\n- Many firms require a second-level approval:\n  - Status: “Pending Approval”.\n  - Supervisor/authorizer reviews and either approves or rejects.\n- Once approved, status changes to “Authorized” and the order is eligible for routing.\n\n**External routing:**\n- Order Management System (OMS) sends the order to:\n  - An exchange-based MF platform, or\n  - Directly to the fund’s Registrar & Transfer Agent (RTA) via API/file.\n- Message typically includes:\n  - Scheme code, folio/account, amount/units.\n  - Transaction type, fresh vs. additional purchase, client identifiers.\n\n**Cut-off time control:**\n- Orders approved and routed **before fund cut-off** (e.g., 3:00 PM) get **same-day NAV**.\n- Orders after cut-off get **next business day NAV**.\n- Systems often use an internal cut-off earlier than the official one to allow processing time.\n\n**External references:**\n- On successful placement, the RTA (or exchange platform) returns an external transaction ID (e.g., **RTA Ref No.**), which is stored against the order for tracking.\n\nIf routing fails (API down, connectivity issues), the order may remain in an “Authorized but not sent” or “In Progress” state and be retried or escalated.\n\n---\n\n## 5. NAV Pricing & Unit Allocation\n\nPricing is based on the **Net Asset Value (NAV)** for the applicable trade date.\n\n**Before execution:**\n- System uses latest available NAV feeds to:\n  - Show indicative NAV.\n  - Estimate units = amount / last known NAV.\n- This is only indicative; final units depend on the official closing NAV.\n\n**At execution (RTA side):**\n- Trade date is determined by when the order reached the RTA vs. cut-off.\n- RTA calculates:\n  - Final NAV used.\n  - Exact units (for purchases) or amount (for redemptions).\n\n**Back in the wealth system:**\n- RTA sends confirmation with:\n  - Executed NAV.\n  - Units/amount.\n  - Trade date and reference numbers.\n- System updates the order with actual execution details.\n- Controls check for:\n  - Missing/stale NAV.\n  - Unusual price/unit discrepancies (beyond rounding tolerances), which are flagged for review.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Settlement with RTA / Custodian\n\nAfter execution, the transaction settles and records are updated.\n\n**Typical settlement timelines:**\n- Purchases: units allotted on T or T+1.\n- Redemptions: proceeds credited on T+1/T+2/T+3 depending on fund type and market.\n\n**Purchases:**\n- Cash is debited from client’s bank (via payment gateway, mandate, or bank integration) around order execution.\n- On settlement:\n  - RTA allots units to the investor’s folio.\n  - RTA’s records become the official unit-holder register.\n\n**Redemptions:**\n- Units are extinguished in the folio.\n- RTA credits redemption proceeds directly to the registered bank account.\n\n**System updates:**\n- Wealth system receives a **trade confirmation/contract note file** from RTA:\n  - Final units/amount.\n  - Settlement date.\n  - RTA reference numbers.\n- Order status is updated to **Settled/Completed**.\n- Client holdings are updated:\n  - Purchases: units added.\n  - Redemptions: units reduced.\n\nIf the RTA rejects the order, it is marked as **Failed/Rejected** with reason codes.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Post-Settlement Processing & Reconciliation\n\nOperations teams (or automated jobs) reconcile internal records with RTA data.\n\n**Transaction reconciliation:**\n- Match each internal order with RTA confirmation using:\n  - Scheme code.\n  - Folio number.\n  - Transaction reference.\n  - Units/amount and dates.\n- Outcomes:\n  - **Matched**: all key fields align.\n  - **Differential match**: minor differences (e.g., rounding) within tolerance.\n  - **Unmatched/Exception**: no corresponding record or material differences.\n\n**New folios:**\n- For fresh purchases, RTA may create a new folio number.\n- Reconciliation logic:\n  - Identifies that the RTA record matches an internal order (by client, scheme, amount, date).\n  - Updates the internal record with the **new folio number**.\n  - Marks the order as matched and completed.\n\n**Exception handling in reconciliation:**\n- Unmatched items:\n  - RTA record with no internal order (out-of-band transaction).\n  - Internal order with no RTA confirmation.\n- These are flagged for manual investigation and correction.\n\nAfter reconciliation, the wealth system’s holdings are treated as synchronized with RTA records.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Exception Handling & Remediation\n\nExceptions can occur at multiple stages.\n\n**Validation/compliance failures:**\n- Immediate feedback to user (e.g., “KYC not valid”, “Minimum amount not met”).\n- Order cannot proceed until corrected.\n\n**Payment failures (purchases):**\n- **Business rejections** (e.g., insufficient funds, incorrect account):\n  - Order marked **Failed** with specific reason.\n- **Technical failures** (e.g., network/API errors):\n  - Order kept in “In Progress” or similar status.\n  - System retries debits and/or queries bank/payment status periodically.\n  - If still unresolved near cut-off, order is marked **Failed** to avoid late submission.\n\n**RTA-level failures:**\n- RTA rejects order due to data issues, limits, or regulatory reasons.\n- Status updated to “Rejected by RTA” with reason code.\n- In baskets, some legs may succeed while others fail; each order is tracked individually.\n\n**Operational remediation:**\n- For persistent technical issues, operations may:\n  - Manually upload orders to RTA/exchange portals.\n  - Manually correct data and re-book where allowed.\n\nClients and internal teams are typically notified (email/SMS/alerts) when orders fail or are rejected.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Audit Trails, Approvals & Governance\n\nStrong governance is embedded throughout the lifecycle.\n\n**Maker-checker approvals:**\n- Front-office (maker) enters orders.\n- Approver (checker) reviews:\n  - Client, scheme, amount, risk flags, exceptions.\n- Approver can:\n  - Approve → status changes to “Authorized”.\n  - Reject → order canceled, not routed.\n\n**Escalated approvals:**\n- For exceptions (e.g., product risk > client risk, large ticket sizes), additional approvals may be required:\n  - Compliance officer.\n  - Senior manager / regional head.\n\n**Audit trail:**\n- Every significant action is logged:\n  - Who created, modified, approved, or rejected the order.\n  - Timestamps for each action.\n  - Old vs. new values where applicable.\n  - Status changes (e.g., Pending → Authorized → Sent → Settled/Failed).\n- Logs are tamper-resistant and retained for regulatory timeframes.\n\nThis ensures full traceability for internal governance and external audits.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Reporting & Regulatory Records\n\nThe final stage focuses on communication and long-term record-keeping.\n\n**Client reporting:**\n- Real-time notifications:\n  - Order placement acknowledgments.\n  - Execution/settlement confirmations.\n  - Rejection/failure notices.\n- Periodic reports:\n  - Portfolio statements showing updated MF holdings.\n  - Transaction statements.\n\n**Internal reporting:**\n- Order book dashboards:\n  - All orders with status (Pending, Authorized, Sent, Settled, Failed).\n  - Filters by client, RM, scheme, date, etc.\n- Reconciliation and exception reports for operations.\n- Management and risk reports (e.g., volumes, exceptions, breaches).\n\n**Regulatory records & retention:**\n- Long-term storage of:\n  - Order details and confirmations.\n  - Audit logs (maker/checker, overrides).\n  - Client communications (where required).\n- Retention aligned with regulations (e.g., 5–7+ years).\n- Ability to export data (CSV, PDF, etc.) for regulators or auditors.\n- Generation of regulatory reports (e.g., periodic trade reports, tax/FATCA-related reports) in prescribed formats.\n\n---\n\n**In summary:**  \nThe mutual fund order management lifecycle runs from order capture and validation, through compliance checks, approvals, routing, NAV-based execution, settlement and reconciliation, to exception handling, audit, and reporting. Each stage is supported by specific data elements, system interfaces (OMS, RTA, custodians, NAV feeds, payment systems), and controls (cut-off times, risk/suitability rules, maker-checker, soft/hard stops, and detailed audit trails).', 'resp_0dfde5da6d5af33700693db3755f7c8192a9158563f6104073', NULL, '{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"classifier","confidence":0.08,"matchedKeywords":["mutual fund"]},"jobId":"job_1765651319415_3j8nnn63b","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_0dfde5da6d5af33700693db3755f7c8192a9158563f6104073"}', '2025-12-13 18:41:58.999919'),
('226', '84', 'user', 'How does a user secure their access to the application immediately after completing email verification?', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-12-16 10:43:31.747625'),
('227', '84', 'assistant', '## Secure Access Immediately After Email Verification\n\n### 1. Transition from Email Verification to Authenticated Session\n\n1. **Email verification via OTP or link**  \n   - The user provides the email address and receives a one-time code or verification link.  \n   - The user must correctly enter the OTP or access the link within a defined validity window to complete verification .\n\n2. **No direct full access on verification alone**  \n   - Email verification is treated as **identity proofing** for the channel, not as a full login.  \n   - After successful verification, the user is redirected to the login/credential‑setup step rather than being silently logged into a full session.\n\n### 2. Required Authentication Steps After Email Verification\n\nImmediately after email verification, the recommended flow is:\n\n1. **Initial credential setup or confirmation**  \n   - If this is a first‑time user: prompt to **set a strong password/PIN** that meets policy (length, complexity, disallow reuse, etc.).  \n   - If the user already has credentials: prompt a **standard login** (user ID + password) using the now-verified email for account association.\n\n2. **Multi‑Factor Authentication (MFA)**  \n   - For first login after email verification, enforce **step‑up MFA** (OTP to mobile/email, or app-based token) in addition to password.  \n   - The same OTP pattern as used in onboarding (e.g., send OTP, user inputs OTP on verification screen) can be reused for MFA, but with distinct purpose/labels .\n\n3. **Session creation only after successful password + MFA**  \n   - An authenticated application session is established **only after both** password authentication and MFA succeed.  \n   - Prior steps (email verification screens) run in a pre‑auth, limited session that does not expose customer or portfolio data.\n\n### 3. Session Management Immediately Post‑Verification\n\n1. **Session start and scope**  \n   - The authenticated session starts once the user completes password login and mandatory MFA.  \n   - Default session scope should provide access to general dashboards and non-transactional views, with **separate step‑up prompts for high‑risk actions** (e.g., order placement, changes to risk profile, entitlements).\n\n2. **Session timeout and idle limits**  \n   - Set a **shorter idle timeout** for the **first session after email verification** (e.g., 5–10 minutes of inactivity) to limit exposure if the environment or device is not yet trusted.  \n   - Enforce an **absolute session lifetime** regardless of activity (e.g., 30–60 minutes) before re‑authentication is required for any further access.\n\n3. **Re-authentication for sensitive actions**  \n   - Before the user performs security‑sensitive or risk‑sensitive actions (e.g., changing contact details, submitting a high‑risk purchase order), prompt for:  \n     - Password re‑entry and/or  \n     - Another OTP/app‑based factor.  \n   - This aligns with risk‑based controls already defined for product and customer risk, where deviations trigger warnings or hard stops during order journeys .\n\n### 4. Device and Risk-Based Access Controls\n\n1. **Basic device and channel checks**  \n   - Tag the device/browser at the time of the first post‑verification login (user agent, IP, geo metadata).  \n   - If the device/geo appears anomalous vs. typical usage, **force MFA** even if the user later marks the device as trusted.\n\n2. **Trusted device flag with constraints**  \n   - Optionally allow the user to mark a device as **trusted** (e.g., suppress some MFA prompts for low‑risk actions).  \n   - Even on trusted devices, **always require MFA** for high‑risk actions like placing orders in products with higher product risk profile than the customer’s risk profile or modifying key profile attributes .\n\n3. **Risk-aware access controls**  \n   - Ensure that once logged in, all transactional screens (e.g., purchase/order flows) continue to apply **risk profile validations**, preventing orders where product risk exceeds the customer’s risk tolerance beyond allowed thresholds .  \n   - Alert and notification configurations for risk mismatches and exceptional cases (e.g., product risk > customer risk by X levels) should remain active from the very first session .\n\n### 5. Role-Based Access and Entitlements\n\n1. **Role derivation post-verification**  \n   - Upon authenticated login, the system resolves the user’s **role and entitlements** (e.g., customer, RM, supervisor) from central maintenance/definition modules .  \n   - Screens, menus, and actions exposed in this first session must strictly follow these entitlements.\n\n2. **Segregation of duties and approvals**  \n   - For actions that require additional approvals (e.g., orders with higher risk deviation), ensure the same multi‑level authorization logic applies from the first post‑verification session, routing orders to supervisors or heads as configured .\n\n### 6. System-Generated Communication and Notifications\n\n1. **Confirmation mails/messages**  \n   - After email verification and first successful authenticated access, send a **system-generated notification** (email/SMS/in‑app) confirming:  \n     - Email verified successfully.  \n     - Date/time and channel of first secure login.\n\n2. **Security alerts**  \n   - If an unusual device/location is detected, generate alerts to the user and/or internal monitoring teams, using the existing alert/notification framework that also handles product‑risk and exception alerts .\n\n### 7. Logging and Audit Requirements\n\nDuring the immediate post‑email‑verification period, ensure that the following events are fully logged and auditable:\n\n1. **Verification and authentication events**  \n   - Email verification request and outcome (success/failure) with timestamp and channel .  \n   - Password setup/change events.  \n   - All login attempts, MFA challenges, and results.\n\n2. **Session lifecycle events**  \n   - Session creation (with correlation to email-verified identity).  \n   - Session termination due to explicit logout, idle timeout, or absolute timeout.\n\n3. **Security‑relevant actions**  \n   - Changes to customer profile that affect risk assessment, limits, or contact details (based on defined maintenance and role modules) .  \n   - Any order or purchase attempts where product risk is higher than customer risk, including triggered warnings, hard stops, and approvals  .\n\n4. **Entitlement and configuration changes (back-office)**  \n   - Although not done by the end user during this session, any changes to roles, service groups, or alert definitions that could affect how the user is controlled should also be audited in the same ecosystem .\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nImmediately after email verification, the application should:\n\n- Treat verification as a **pre‑auth step**, not a full login.  \n- Require **password authentication plus MFA** before creating a full session.  \n- Start a **tightly controlled initial session** (short idle and absolute timeouts), with step‑up re‑authentication for sensitive actions.  \n- Apply **risk-aware validations** (e.g., product vs. customer risk profile) and standard role-based entitlements from the first session  .  \n- Generate **system notifications** for verification and first secure login, and comprehensively **log/audit** all verification, authentication, session, and risk-relevant actions.\n\n### Sources\n\n[1] HSBC_DIY_Journey of Customer Onboarding V10.pdf  \n[2] IIFL_Journey of Defining Maintenance_V10_CCV13_Part 1.pdf  \n[3] 360One_Journey of Creating Model Portfolio_V11_CCV13.pdf  \n[4] SBI_Journey of Defining Maintenances__V10.pdf  \n[5] SBI_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF V10_SBI_CCV13.pdf', 'd91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["OTP verification screen","Login","User Office Landing Screen","system generated mail","Notification to User screen"],"seed_node_ids":["system:generated_mail","report:login","dataentity:login","report:otp_verification_screen","report:user_office_landing_screen","report:notification_to_user_screen"],"expanded_nodes":16,"expanded_edges":639,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: d91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"these\\", \\"the above\\")\\n• If such references exist, identify what they refer to based on the conversation history\\n• Internally clarify the question to make it self-contained and explicit\\n\\nSTEP 2 - Focused Response Generation:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: How does a user secure their access to the application immediately after completing email verification?","What is the recommended secure access flow for a user immediately after successful email verification in the application?","Describe the post-email-verification access security flow for a user in the wealth-management application, including: required authentication steps after email verification (MFA, password status), session creation and duration, device risk assessment or trusted devices, prompts for re-authentication, role-based access controls, and logging/audit considerations for the immediate post-verification access period.","Previous context ID: d91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Qu