ase follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"these\\", \\"the above\\")\\n• If such references exist, identify what they refer to based on the conversation history\\n• Internally clarify the question to make it self-contained and explicit\\n\\nSTEP 2 - Focused Response Generation:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: How does a user secure their access to the application immediately after completing email verification? Customer Profile Desk","Order CONTAINS Login","Name DISPLAYED_ON security","Flow Diagram CONTAINS Login","SIP TRANSFORMS security"],"kg_vector_store_id":"vs_6934751b8a90819190113fe85b689848","doc_vector_store_id":"vs_6910a0f29b548191befd180730d968ee","intent_route":"hybrid","intent_hops":2,"domain":"wealth_management","vectorstore_id":"vs_6910a0f29b548191befd180730d968ee","response_id":"d91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5","is_conversational":true,"previous_response_id":"d91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5","processing_time_seconds":120.27,"request_id":"d68e3863-01a1-4e04-b400-c6a2009ffee8","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"conversation","confidence":1,"matchedKeywords":[]}}', '2025-12-16 10:49:14.268619'),
('230', '84', 'user', 'What logic does the system use to sort the list of Relationship Managers when displaying their lead performance?', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-12-16 10:52:16.211477'),
('231', '84', 'assistant', '## RM lead/performance views – sorting logic for Relationship Managers\n\n### 1. Is there a dedicated "RM lead‑performance" list and its sort logic?\nIn the available specifications, RM dashboards and customer dashboards describe how data related to customers, activities, alerts, and notes can be filtered and sorted, but they **do not define a dedicated screen that ranks or lists Relationship Managers by lead performance with a specific multi‑field sorting logic** (e.g., conversion rate, pipeline value, activity recency).\n\nDocuments for RM dashboards focus on:\n- RM viewing and sorting their *own* activities (e.g., To‑Dos by status or date) \n- Supervisors and RMs accessing dashboards and self/supervisor assessment journeys, but without detailing an RM‑by‑RM performance ranking sort order\n\nGiven the available material, there is **no explicit, standardised sorting algorithm documented for an RM list ordered by lead performance** (no stated primary metric, direction, or tie‑break fields).\n\n### 2. Documented sorting behaviour in related views\nWhile the RM lead‑performance list itself is not specified, several related patterns are documented that show how sorting is generally handled in dashboards:\n\n1. **Customer lists on customer dashboards**\n   - Users can sort customers in **ascending or descending order by customer name (alphabetical)**. This is explicitly mentioned for customer lists in customer dashboards, where filters exist for RM/Agent name, AUM, and other attributes, and a generic "Sort" option sorts by name.  \n   - This suggests that where no explicit performance ranking is defined, the default pattern is a simple, user‑initiated sort by an identifier (typically name) with direction toggle.\n\n2. **Activity and notes lists on RM dashboards**\n   - To‑Do items can be **sorted by status or date**, with the RM choosing the sort criterion; this is a per‑widget, user‑driven sort rather than a fixed business ranking. \n   - Notes can also be sorted (criteria not deeply specified, but pattern is that the user selects the sort option on the widget). \n\nThese patterns indicate that, in similar list‑type widgets, sorting is **simple, single‑field, and often user‑selectable**, not multi‑metric ranking with complex tie‑break rules.\n\n### 3. What can be stated about RM lead‑performance sorting\nBased on the above and the absence of a specific RM ranking spec:\n\n- **Primary sort field and direction:**\n  - No document defines a standard primary sort like "lead conversion rate (descending)" or "number of leads (descending)" for an RM list.\n  - Where analogous lists exist (customers), the default user‑triggered sort is by **name, ascending or descending**; for activities, by **status or date**.   \n  - It is therefore reasonable to infer that, **unless your implementation has a custom BRD**, an RM list on such a view would typically default to either:\n    - Alphabetical by RM name, or\n    - A simple metric such as total leads or AUM, if configured locally.\n  - However, **this is not codified in the shared documents**, so any concrete metric‑based ordering must come from project‑specific configuration, not the generic standard.\n\n- **Tie‑break logic (e.g., conversion rate, pipeline value, recency):**\n  - No tie‑breaker hierarchy is specified anywhere for a list of RMs (e.g., "if conversion rate is equal, then sort by total pipeline, then by name").\n\n- **Configurability of sorting (user vs admin):**\n  - Related widgets (customers, To‑Dos, notes) allow the **end user to pick the sort criterion** (e.g., status vs date, ascending vs descending, by name).   \n  - There is **no explicit configuration section** describing admin‑level controls to define or lock the default RM ranking logic for lead performance.\n\n- **Influence of filters (region, time window, etc.):**\n  - Filters on dashboards (HNW, AUM, product type, RM/Agent name) clearly **constrain which customers or records are displayed**, but do **not alter the underlying sort rule**; sort and filter are independent actions in the described screens.  \n  - By analogy, regional or time‑window filters on an RM lead‑performance view would typically **change the dataset (which RMs or which leads are counted)**, while the ranking rule (whatever is configured) remains the same.\n\n- **Data sources for any RM performance ranking:**\n  - The broader ecosystem uses **leads, opportunities, activities, and customer holdings** as sources for RM‑level metrics (e.g., opportunities from call reports, alerts, AUM and product composition on dashboards).  \n  - However, the documents stop short of stating a specific formula for a composite "lead performance" score or its direct use in sorting RMs.\n\n### 4. Practical conclusion\nGiven the current documentation set:\n\n- **There is no standard, documented system logic that definitively states how RMs are sorted in a dedicated “lead‑performance” RM list (no fixed primary metric, direction, or tie‑breakers).**\n- Existing patterns show:\n  - **Simple, single‑field sorts** (mostly by name, date, or status), chosen by the user in each widget.   \n  - **Filters** that affect what records appear, but not the sort mechanism itself.\n- Therefore, if your environment shows a ranked list of RMs by lead performance, the ordering is most likely **defined in a project‑specific BRD or configuration (e.g., custom KPI weighting or supervisor‑view logic)** rather than in the base product specification.\n\nFor an accurate answer in your specific instance, you would need to refer to your implementation’s BRD/FRD or configuration notes that define:\n- Which KPI (or composite score) is used as the primary sort, and\n- Any secondary metrics or name‑based tie‑break rules applied on that screen.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n[1] JioBlackRock_Journey of Self Assessment and Supervisor Assessment - RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10.pdf  \n[2] SAAB-Journey of Self_Assessment and Supervisor Assessment_Customer Dashboard_V13_CCV10docx.pdf  \n[3] Maybank_Journey of Self-Assessment and Supervisor Assessment-Customer Dashboard_V12_CCV_V10docx.pdf', 'd91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["RM","Lead","Relationship","Portfolio Performance Report","Customer Dashboard","Risk Profile Deviation alert"],"seed_node_ids":["report:customer_dashboard","dataentity:relationship","report:pf_performance_report","system:rmws","report:risk_profile_deviation_alert","dataentity:lead","dataentity:rm"],"expanded_nodes":39,"expanded_edges":1180,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: d91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"these\\", \\"the above\\")\\n• If such references exist, identify what they refer to based on the conversation history\\n• Internally clarify the question to make it self-contained and explicit\\n\\nSTEP 2 - Focused Response Generation:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: What logic does the system use to sort the list of Relationship Managers when displaying their lead performance?","What are the rules or criteria used to sort Relationship Managers in the lead-performance display, including any configurable sort fields, direction, and tie-break logic?","On the Relationship Manager lead-performance screen, what sorting logic does the system apply 