('213', '82', 'user', 'What actions can a user perform to test campaign communications before they are broadcasted to customers?', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-12-16 07:19:34.777892'),
('214', '82', 'assistant', '## Overview\n\nBefore campaign communications are broadcasted to customers, users typically have a set of **testing, validation and approval capabilities**. These are designed to ensure the right content goes to the right audience in the right format, and that all activities are auditable.\n\nBelow is a consolidated, platform‑agnostic view of such capabilities.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Previewing Campaign Communications\n\nUsers can generate and view previews of campaign messages before sending:\n\n- **Channel‑specific previews** – For each selected channel (Email, SMS, etc.), the user can open a preview screen to see the exact subject, body, and layout that will be sent. Campaign communication screens already distinguish and allow separate handling of Email and SMS broadcasts  .\n- **Multi‑device / multi‑client rendering checks** – For emails, users can view how the message renders in desktop vs mobile layouts. For SMS/push, they can verify character counts, truncation, and link formatting.\n- **Audience‑context preview** – Users can preview how the message will appear for a sample customer (e.g., using a test profile) to verify personalization fields.\n\n**Expected outcome:** The user confirms that content, layout, and basic formatting are correct for each channel and target device before any live send.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Test Sends to Internal Recipients\n\nUsers can perform controlled test sends before a full broadcast:\n\n- **Send to internal email addresses** – From the campaign communication screen, the user can initiate an email send to designated internal test mailboxes, similar to how they trigger regular Email communication via a dedicated "Send Mail" action .\n- **Send to internal test mobile numbers** – For SMS campaigns, users can send test messages to internal or test mobile numbers using the same Send SMS function used for live broadcasts, but restricted to a test audience .\n- **Test push/in‑app notifications** – For push or in‑app messages, a limited test group (e.g., internal users or test devices) can be configured to receive trial notifications.\n\n**Expected outcome:** The team validates deliverability, subject lines, links, and visual behavior in real clients before including actual customers.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Validation of Personalization and Dynamic Fields\n\nCampaigns often contain personalized tokens and dynamic content (e.g., customer name, portfolio metrics). Before broadcasting, the system supports validation such as:\n\n- **Placeholder resolution checks** – In preview or test sends, the system resolves personalization tokens (e.g., customer name, RM name, product details) against sample records to ensure they render correctly and do not show raw placeholders.\n- **Data availability checks** – If a required data point for personalization is missing for a customer, validations or warnings are raised, analogous to general and field‑level validations used in other journeys .\n\n**Expected outcome:** Messages display complete, correct personalized information; missing data is identified and handled (fallback text or exclusion) before live broadcast.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Content and Compliance Validations\n\nBefore a campaign is allowed to move to broadcast, the platform typically runs a set of validations similar to those used in transaction journeys:\n\n- **Mandatory fields validation** – Ensures that mandatory fields such as subject, body text, channel selection, and target audience are populated, analogous to mandatory field checks in order placement .\n- **Format and content rules** – Validates that key fields conform to format rules (e.g., no prohibited special characters in subject lines, valid URLs, character limits for SMS).\n- **Compliance checks** – Verifies that opt‑in/consent flags are respected and that communications are aligned with customer contact preferences, similar in spirit to general validations and actor/entitlement controls defined for other journeys .\n\n**Expected outcome:** The system blocks or warns on non‑compliant or incomplete campaigns, forcing corrections before approval or broadcast.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Multi‑Channel Formatting and Consistency Checks\n\nFor campaigns sent across multiple channels (Email + SMS + push):\n\n- **Channel‑specific templates** – Users verify that each channel’s template is appropriately tailored (e.g., shortened SMS content vs richer email content), using the separate send actions for Email and SMS on the campaign communication screen .\n- **Cross‑channel consistency** – Users confirm that core message, key disclosures, and call‑to‑action are consistent across channels, even if format differs.\n\n**Expected outcome:** Each channel presents a fit‑for‑purpose version of the message, while keeping the underlying intent and disclosures consistent.\n\n---\n\n## 6. A/B Testing and Variant Comparison (Where Enabled)\n\nSome platforms support A/B or multivariate testing before full roll‑out:\n\n- **Variant creation** – Users create multiple content variants (different subject lines, layouts, or call‑to‑action).\n- **Test group selection** – A small portion of the target audience or an internal test group is assigned to each variant.\n- **Performance comparison** – Based on open/click/response metrics (for the test window), the best‑performing variant is selected for the main broadcast.\n\n**Expected outcome:** Campaigns are optimized based on measured performance before large‑scale send.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Staging / Test Environment Usage\n\nTo further minimize risk, users can:\n\n- **Configure and run campaigns in a non‑production (staging) environment** – Mirroring production data structures but with masked or synthetic data.\n- **Dry‑run workflows** – Execute the full lifecycle (design → preview → test send → approval) without any real customer impact.\n\n**Expected outcome:** Complex or high‑impact campaigns are validated end‑to‑end in a safe environment before being recreated or promoted to production.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Approval and "To Approve" Workflows\n\nSimilar to transaction journeys where orders created by one user must be approved by a supervisor via a **To Approve** tab and order card details , campaigns typically leverage parallel approval patterns:\n\n- **Draft vs. Ready‑for‑Approval states** – Users prepare and validate the campaign (content, audience, tests) and then mark it as ready for approval.\n- **Supervisor / QA review queue** – Approvers access a dedicated "To Approve" or equivalent tab, where pending campaigns appear much like pending orders. They can expand each item to review content, audience, and validation results before approving or rejecting .\n- **Entitlement‑based access** – Only users with the required approval entitlement can authorize broadcasts, aligning with the actor/entitlement framework used in other journeys .\n\n**Expected outcome:** No campaign is broadcasted without explicit approval from an authorized user; the process is controlled and governed.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Broadcast Status, Outcomes, and Logging\n\nOnce campaigns are tested and approved, the system tracks and exposes status and logs:\n\n- **Broadcast status tracking** – The campaign communication screen displays the broadcast status of Email and SMS communications, allowing users to confirm whether a send is pending, in progress, completed, or failed  .\n- **Activity and audit logs** – Key actions—such as content changes, test sends, approval decisions, and final broadcasts—are logged with timestamps and user identifiers, following the same auditability principles as order and approval journeys .\n- **Error handling and retry** – If any part of the broadcast fails (e.g., channel gateway issues), the system captures errors and may trigger retry mechanisms or alerts to users.\n\n**Expected outcome:** Users have clear visibility into what was sent, to whom, when, and by whom, with an audit trail supporting internal and regulatory reviews.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Summary of User Actions Before Broadcast\n\nIn practical terms, a user can typically perform the following actions before sending campaign communications to customers:\n\n1. Design or upload content for each channel.\n2. Preview the message per channel and device.\n3. Validate personalization and dynamic fields using sample profiles.\n4. Run automated validations for mandatory fields, formats, and compliance.\n5. Send test messages to internal email addresses and test mobile numbers.\n6. (Optionally) Run A/B tests on content variants with a limited audience.\n7. Execute end‑to‑end dry runs in a staging/test environment.\n8. Submit the campaign into an approval workflow.\n9. Have supervisors/QA review and approve via a To Approve–style queue.\n10. Monitor broadcast status and consult logs after or during the send.\n\nThese capabilities together ensure that campaign communications are **accurate, compliant, tested, and properly approved** before they reach end customers.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n- [1] SBI_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV13.pdf – Campaign communication screens, Email/SMS actions, and broadcast status behavior.\n- [2] 360One_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV10docx.pdf – Campaign communication journey and Send Mail/Send SMS options.\n- [3] 360ONE_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV13_Part 4.pdf – To Approve tab and supervisor approval patterns for orders.\n- [4] HSBC_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV10_Part 1.pdf – General validations, field‑level details, and actor/entitlement concepts applied in transactional flows.', 'd76a1db5-04aa-4e7c-b146-e1132c549c20', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["Flag = \\"Y\\" but QTY is provided","QTY is Mandatory when Full Switch/Redemption flag = \\"Y\\"","QTY is mandatory with TOTALORDERAMT for \\"Amount\\"-based orders","all three fields (IP Address, IP Address Date, IP Address Time) are mandatory","format of IP Address Date (DDMMYYYY)","mandator