('176', '76', 'assistant', 'Drawdown: definition and application support\n\nDefinition of drawdown\n- Drawdown refers to the decline from a prior peak to a trough in the value of an investment or security over a given period. In practice, this is described as the peak-to-trough decline and is used as a measure of downside risk [1].\n\nApplication support for drawdown\n- The platform provides a dedicated drawdown metric through the Max Drawdown capability, which is displayed on the View Performance Graph as Max Drawdown. This metric represents the maximum observed loss from a peak to a trough for defined horizons (1M, 3M, 6M, 1Y, 2Y, 5Y) and is calculated using price data maintained in the Security Price Master [1]. In practice, this appears as a screen titled View Performance Graph – Max Drawdown [1], and is referenced across multiple journeys as the mechanism to display drawdown information [2].\n- Backtesting contexts also reference drawdown in conjunction with performance projection and max drawdown calculations, with annexures documenting the calculation methodology and sample calculations (e.g., Backtesting, Performance Projection and Max Drawdown) [3], [4], [5].\n\nWhere drawdown appears and data inputs\n- Where it appears: Max Drawdown appears on the View Performance Graph screen as a dedicated graph (View Performance Graph – Max Drawdown) [1], [2].\n- Data inputs: The calculation is grounded in prices from the Security Price Master, i.e., drawdown is plotted based on these prices [1].\n\nEnablement, configuration, and limitations\n- Enablement/configuration: Documentation references annexures that describe how drawdown is calculated and present sample calculations (Backtesting, Performance Projection, and Max Drawdown). This indicates the capability is embedded in the standard performance graph tooling and is documented via annexures rather than a separate toggle [3], [5].\n- Limitations: The available excerpts do not explicitly enumerate operational limitations or step-by-step enablement instructions beyond the existence of the Max Drawdown graph and annexure calculations; explicit export options are not described in the cited materials [5].\n\nRelation to backtesting and related concepts\n- Backtesting functionality is described as part of the performance view, with references to backtesting displays and calculations, and annexures detailing how backtesting and max drawdown are computed [3], [4], [5].\n\nNotes on related domains\n- Drawdown concepts feature in other contexts (e.g., trade capture and risk-related accounting) as part of the broader investment workflow, illustrating that drawdown-related calculations are part of the instrumented risk and performance tooling in practice [7].\n\nSources\n- Maybank_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF_V12_CCV10_Part 1.pdf [1]\n- 360ONE_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV13_Part 1.pdf [2]\n- HSBC_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV10_Part 1.pdf [3]\n- Maybank_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF_V12_CCV10_Part 2.pdf [4]\n- HSBC_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV10_Part 2.pdf [5]\n- SBI International_Heldaway and trade capture_V10_CCV10.pdf [6]', '9b9cb116-e58d-4f0f-a872-c8fb51fe4fe5', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Max Drawdown"],"seed_node_ids":["aum:max_drawdown","report:warning_display"],"expanded_nodes":12,"expanded_edges":387,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: What is drawdown? Is it supported b