('194', '81', 'assistant', 'End-to-end testing actions for campaign communications (across channels such as email, SMS, and push) before distribution should follow a disciplined, multi-step workflow. The following actions are evidenced in documented campaign-related journeys and QA practices:\n\n1) Create and configure test draft campaigns\n- Build the campaign content and save it in draft mode so it can be reviewed and modified before final deployment. This draft capability is demonstrated as a standard step in campaign management journeys, including an option to Save as Draft for later modification [1].\n\n2) Preview and render across channels/devices\n- Use a Preview function to view the email details of the campaign before sending, ensuring the content layout and placeholders render correctly. Preview capabilities are explicitly described for email campaigns, enabling reviewers to inspect the message prior to broadcast [1].\n- Preview capabilities are similarly described in other campaign journeys, reinforcing the importance of seeing the exact message as it would appear to recipients [2].\n\n3) Content and personalization token validation\n- Campaign content often relies on personalization tokens (placeholders) such as account numbers, dates, and other dynamic fields. Verifying that these tokens render with the correct data in the preview confirms appropriate personalization logic before sending [1].\n\n4) Review and approvals workflows\n- Governance around campaigns includes approvals workflows (maker-checker style) as part of campaign/order journey governance, indicating formal review steps before deployment [3].\n\n5) QA-oriented test scenarios and validation patterns\n- Documented test scenarios exist for related journey components, illustrating a structured approach to validating flows before production, which can be applied to testing campaign communications (e.g., initiating test journeys, handling version mismatches, and ensuring proper progression through steps) [3].\n\nNotes and scope considerations:\n- The cited sources primarily illustrate draft, preview, and approval capabilities for campaign-related content, with explicit examples focusing on email previews and token usage. Where multi-channel-specific testing (SMS/push) is referenced, the general testing pattern—draft, preview, token validation, approvals—remains applicable across channels as a best-practice framework.\n- If you require explicit steps for test audience selection, internal test sends, and delivery-window simulations across email, SMS, and push, those capabilities are commonly aligned with the same governance and preview constructs shown in the sources, and would be implemented as extensions of the draft/preview/approval workflow described above.\n\nSources\n- 360One_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV10docx.pdf\n- HSBC_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV13docx.pdf\n- EID031 - Model Portfolio_Basket Based Investments.docx', '9822b9a5-a913-4ac0-b74b-397d8ecaf176', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Wealth Qube","system generated mail","broker","User Office","Transact Journey","SIP Scheduler","Supervisor Approval screen","To Approve tab","Mutual Fund - Input SWP Details","Mutual Fund - Mode of Transaction"],"seed_node_ids":["system:user_office","dataentity:warning_message","report:mutual_fund_input_sip_details","report:performance_projection","dataentity:broker","report:mutual_fund_mode_transaction","system:to_approve_tab","system:generated_mail","system:mutual_fund_mode_transaction","system:broker","system:transact_journey","system:mutual_fund_input_swp_details","system:supervisor_approval_screen","system:sip_scheduler","system:wealth_qube"],"expanded_nodes":41,"expanded_edges":50,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: 9822b9a5-a913-4ac0-b74b-397d8ecaf176\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please 