('210', '81', 'assistant', 'Sorting RM lead-performance lists is described in terms of how data is organized and filtered for display, with explicit details on grouping and the data sources involved, but the documents do not provide a single, explicit, fixed rule set for primary/secondary ranking, tie-breakers, or the exact server/client sorting implementation. The observed elements are:\n\n- Data is grouped by RM name for lead-performance context and related parameters when viewed on dashboards, indicating RM-level aggregation forms the basis of ordering decisions [2].\n- Dashboards support filtering by a time frame, which directly affects which performance data are displayed for each RM; the time frame selection governs the data slice used in any ranking or display [2].\n- The data shown on dashboards is prepared via calculation logic and is aligned to metrics described in accompanying appendices or calculation sections, suggesting that sorting (when it occurs) would be based on these computed performance metrics rather than raw counts [2].\n- Lead-management workflows described in the materials show that lists of customers/leads can be generated or filtered using lead-rule criteria, and that generated lists can be used to drive downstream views of RM performance; this implies that RM sorting could be influenced by the applied lead rules and the resulting lead cohorts [3].\n\nIn summary, while the exact, fixed sorting criteria (e.g., the precise primary and secondary fields, tie-break rules, and implementation details) are not explicitly documented in the retrieved materials, the evidence points to RM-level aggregation, time-frame controlled data, and calculation-driven metrics as the basis for any ordering in lead-performance displays. When concrete rules exist, they would be defined by the calculated metrics (grouped by RM) and the selected time frame, with lead-rule criteria shaping the data that feeds these metrics [2][3].\n\nSources:\n- JioBlackRock_Journey o