('263', '98', 'assistant', 'Asset rebalancing in wealth-management portfolios is guided by a combination of time-based cadences and trigger-based triggers, with frequency being configurable to suit the model and client context.\n\nKey approaches\n- Time-based (periodic) rebalancing: Frequency options are configurable and can include daily, weekly, monthly, or quarterly cadences. This allows a disciplined, regular review cycle for asset allocations to align with the target mix [1].\n- Trigger-based rebalancing: Rebalancing can be system-initiated (auto trigger) or advisor-initiated (manual), enabling rebalancing when predefined conditions are met rather than strictly on a calendar basis [1].\n\nHow drift/deviation informs frequency\n- Asset drift is monitored through deviation and exposure views that compare model allocations to actual holdings (model vs. actual vs. selected asset-class allocations). This drift information is used to determine when rebalancing should be considered, as deviations signal misalignment with the target allocation [2].\n\nFactors shaping the recommended frequency\n- Drift thresholds / deviation levels: The need to rebalance is driven by how far actual allocations have deviated from the model targets, as surfaced by deviation/exposure measurements [2].\n- Risk tolerance and client objectives: The chosen cadence and trigger thresholds reflect the client''s risk appetite and stated goals, which influence how aggressively allocations are kept in line with targets [1].\n- Tax and transaction cost considerations: Frequency and trigger selection balance the desire to maintain target allocations with the potential tax consequences and costs of trading [1].\n- Asset-class behavior and platform governance: The behavior of underlying asset classes and the governance/workflow configuration of the platform (e.g., model order approval workflows) influence how and when rebalancing is executed [1], and how deviations are presented to users for decisioning [2].\n\nPractical takeaway\n- Most wealth-management implementations support both time-based cadences and deviation-driven triggers, with the exact frequency and trigger rules configurable in the model/portfolio setup. This allows tailoring to client objectives, risk tolerance, and cost/tax considerations while maintaining appropriate governance and control over rebalancing actions [1][2].\n\nSources\n- [1] EID031 - Model Portfolio_Basket Based Investments.docx\n- [2] SBI_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF V10_SBI_CCV13.pdf', '9d276133-8a5e-4849-8f57-18f6fac66e04', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Selected Portfolio - Asset Class","Asset Class wise Product Composition","Product Composition – Asset Class","List of Asset Classes","Mutual Fund – View Deviation & Exposure","Portfolio Performance Report","Portfolio View","Mutual Funds","securities","Product Cart"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:asset_class_wise_product_composition","report:mutual_fund_view_deviation_exposure","datastore:product_cart","dataentity:mutual_funds","system:product_cart","dataentity:product_cart","report:selected_pf_asset_class","report:product_composition","dataentity:list_asset_classes","report:pf_view","dataentity:securities","dataentity:product_composition_asset_class","report:product_cart","report:pf_performance_report"],"expanded_nodes":68,"expanded_edges":124,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: How often is asset rebalancing recommended within wealth management portfolios?","What is the recommended frequency for rebalancing client portfolios in wealth management, and what factors determine that frequency?","What is the standard rebalancing frequency for wealth management portfolios, including time-based and trigger-based approaches, and what factors influence this guidance (portfolio drift thresholds, risk tolerance, client objectives, tax and cost considerations, asset-class behavior, and platform governance/workflow implications)?","[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: How often is asset rebalancing recommended within wealth management portfolios? STP","[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: How often is asset rebalancing recommended within wealth management portfolios? Mutual Fund – View Deviation & Exposure","[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize