t":"2025-12-17T13:39:28.945Z"}', '2025-12-17 13:39:29.057134'),
('265', '101', 'assistant', 'Role of the Risk Profile Questionnaire in Shaping Investment Strategies\n\n- What it is and what it yields\n  - The risk profile questionnaire is designed to gauge an investor’s willingness to take risk and their risk-taking capability, with the outcome being a risk profile assigned to the investor based on their responses. This foundational input drives subsequent investment planning and execution steps [1].\n  - The questionnaire is typically structured into three sections—Financial Profiling, Investment Knowledge Profiling, and Risk Profiling—whose combined data produce a quantified risk score and an accompanying risk profile description (the basis for strategy). This tripartite structure and its outputs are described as the core flow for risk assessment and profiling [2].\n\n- How it informs onboarding and risk-tolerance assessment\n  - Onboarding processes navigate to the risk profile questionnaire when no prior risk profile exists, ensuring that a fresh assessment is obtained before any investment actions are taken. This onboarding flow explicitly links the risk profile to the overall client profile (investor onboarding and risk profiling) [1].\n  - On completion, the risk profile and its score are used to determine the recommended risk profile, which feeds downstream decisions such as asset allocation and model-portfolio mapping. Governance and maintenance steps (risk appetite mapping, questionnaire maintenance) are described as prerequisites in the onboarding flow, illustrating the role of the questionnaire in establishing the investor’s risk framework upfront [3].\n  - The risk profile mechanism is integrated with a broader governance model, including mapping to risk appetites and model portfolios, which provides structured checks before execution. Deviation from risk mappings is governed in the order-placement stage, underscoring lifecycle controls for risk alignment [3].\n\n- How it drives asset allocation and model portfolios\n  - The risk profile emerges as the basis for asset-allocation maintenance and the selection of model portfolios. The literature describes a direct linkage: risk profiles drive the asset-allocation framework, and model portfolios are defined to reflect the risk level associated with each profile. This linkage is central to how investment recommendations are calibrated to risk tolerance [4].\n  - Outputs from the risk profile questionnaire include expected return, standard deviation, risk score, and the corresponding model-asset-allocation guidance. These outputs feed the recommended risk profile screen and the set of funds or assets that constitute the model portfolio for that risk tier [2].\n\n- How it informs product recommendations and suitability determinations\n  - The risk profile informs which products and asset classes are suitable for the investor, with the model-portfolio framework serving as the vehicle for translating risk tolerance into a concrete investment mix. Product risk profiles and the corresponding recommended allocations are part of the model-portfolio maintenance workflow, linking risk assessment to product selection and suitability determinations [4].\n\n- Lifecycle governance and review implications\n  - The risk profile serves as a prerequisite for asset-allocation maintenance and model-portfolio setup, with governance steps such as risk appetite mapping and appropriate approvals embedded in the lifecycle. The process explicitly notes that risk profiling and questionnaire maintenance are prerequisites and that deviation from risk alignment is controlled within the order-placement phase, ensuring ongoing risk governance as part of portfolio construction and execution [3].\n  - The lifecycle includes reassessment capabilities (e.g., reassessing risk profile after completing the questionnaire) to ensure the profile remains aligned with current circumstances and investment goals. This reassessment pathway is documented within client-portal flows, illustrating ongoing risk governance and profile updates [6].\n\n- Practical outcomes for the investor journey\n  - The end-to-end flow ties the risk profile questionnaire to the investor’s journey: onboarding, risk assessment, asset allocation, model portfolio maintenance, order placement, and settlement, with risk-profiling data serving as the anchor for each step. The linkage of risk profile outcomes to asset allocation and model portfolios is repeatedly described across risk-assessment and model-portfolio documents, confirming the central role of the questionnaire in shaping strategy and execution [1][2][4].\n\nSources:\n- SBI_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV12.pdf [1]\n- 360One_Journey of Assesing Risk_V10_CCV15.pdf [2]\n- SBI_Journey of Defining Maintenances__V10.pdf [3]\n- 360One_Journey of Creating Model Portfolio_V11_CCV13.pdf [4]\n- SBI_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V10_SBI_CCV13.pdf [5]\n- SBI_Journey of Client Portal_V10_CCV15.pdf [6]', '5930a90e-b52a-46a6-b57b-83519edb3f0c', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["risk profiling","INVESTOR","Journey from Assessing Risk","Risk Profile Deviation alert","KYC Compliance information","KYC","PMS application","India Infoline Wealth","Model Portfolio – Order Placement","Mutual Funds"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:kyc","report:risk_profile_deviation_alert","compliance:risk_profiling","system:india_infoline_wealth","dataentity:risk_profiling","compliance:kyc_compliance_info","dataentity:investor","dataentity:mutual_funds","report:model_pf_order_placement","aum:risk_profiling","system:pms_app"],"expanded_nodes":42,"expanded_edges":86,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely rel