('273', '104', 'assistant', '### 1. Supported fee types / structures\n\nBased on the available documentation, the platform supports the following **revenue and commission-related fee structures**:\n\n1. **Percentage-based trail fees (ongoing commissions)**  \n   * Trail fees are defined as a percentage of assets under management (AUM), typically per scheme and often by category (debt, equity, hybrid etc.).   \n   * Examples include:  \n     - **Perpetual trail fee rate** (ongoing until lot is redeemed, often for SIP/STP transactions).   \n     - **T30 trail fee rate** and **B30 additional trail fee** with scheme- and location-specific percentage rates, subject to conditions like investment amount and investor location.   \n     - **Special trail fee rate** for selected schemes or campaigns.   \n   * These are classic **percentage-of-AUM** fee structures.\n\n2. **Rate-card based percentage brokerage/commission**  \n   * The system maintains **rate cards** for mutual fund commissions/trail fees that can be modified and used for revenue recalculation for prior periods, implying a structured table of percentage-based rates per fund house/scheme.   \n   * Brokerage and trail amounts are then reconciled lot-wise against registrar (RTA/RnTA) files, again as **percentage-based commissions** on each transaction or holding lot. \n\n3. **Positive/negative brokerage for trail and clawback (effective performance/retention adjustment)**  \n   * In reconciliation, **brokerage and clawback** are treated as positive and negative amounts respectively in the same field in RTA files.   \n   * Clawback logic effectively creates a **performance-/behaviour-linked adjustment** (e.g., reversal of previously paid trail if redemption happens within a specified clawback period).  \n\n4. **Location- and time-bound differential trail fees**  \n   * **B30 additional trail fee** is an **incremental percentage trail** applicable only for certain locations (beyond top-30 cities) and within defined investment and time thresholds.   \n   * **T30 trail fees** are the standard trail rates applicable across locations and products, often for a defined number of years, after which the latest rate is used. \n\n> The documents do **not** explicitly describe flat (absolute currency) fees or generic performance-fee formulas (e.g., high-watermark-based incentives for PMS/AIF). The supported and fully specified structures in the available material are **percentage-based trail/brokerage and their clawbacks/adjustments**.\n\n\n### 2. Where fee definitions are configured and managed\n\nThe fee definitions and their lifecycle are distributed across several key configuration and processing points:\n\n#### 2.1. Trail Fee / Rate Card Maintenance (Revenue Desk)\n\n* There is a dedicated **Trail Fee Maintenance** function accessible via the **Revenue Desk**.   \n* Users can:\n  - Maintain **trail fee rates** for different fund houses and schemes (rate card).   \n  - **Create, modify, and delete** trail fee records via specific screens (e.g., “Modify Trail Fee”, “Delete Trail Fee”).   \n  - Submit changes for **Supervisor authorization**, after which the updated rates become effective. \n* The rate card defines, per scheme/fund house (and sometimes per time bucket), the **percentage trail fee** to be applied for revenue computation and reconciliation.  \n\n#### 2.2. Scheme / Security-level Fee Logic\n\n* The **fund house (AMC) and scheme master / security maintenance** store scheme attributes that determine **which fee rules apply**:\n  - Whether a transaction type (Subscription/SIP/STP/Switch) is eligible for a given **trail fee type** (Perpetual, T30, B30, Special).   \n  - For some scenarios (e.g., **Inter Scheme Switch**), schemes can be marked so that **Special trail fees are not computed** for specific transaction types (e.g., Switch-In). This configuration exists as flags under fund house/scheme maintenance. \n* These parameters ensure that, at transaction level, the engine knows **which percentage trail rate to pick** and whether any **additional or special fees** are applicable. \n\n#### 2.3. Trail Fee Computation Engine\n\n* A dedicated **Trail Fee Computation** process calculates:\n  - **Perpetual trail** from SIP/STP transaction date until lot is redeemed.   \n  - **B30 Additional Trail** for eligible locations and only up to one year, subject to investment amount and clawback rules.   \n  - **T30 Trail** for defined tenors (e.g., maximum 5 years, after which the latest rate applies).   \n  - **Special trail** for designated campaigns or schemes (excluding certain switch scenarios as configured). \n* The engine reads the **rate card / trail fee tables** and applies them at **lot level**, considering transaction type, date, scheme, location, and amount. \n\n#### 2.4. Reconciliation with RTA / Reverse Feeds\n\n* The **Trail Fee Reconciliation** component reconciles **lot-wise brokerage information** from the system with **RTA reverse feed files**.   \n* Matching rules typically include AMC code, scheme code, transaction reference number, and brokerage/clawback amounts.   \n* In RTA files, **brokerage and clawback** are represented as positive and negative amounts in the same field; the system interprets these as **trail fee and reversals**.   \n* This reconciliation step validates that **configured fee rates and computed revenue** match external records, and it stores the final, reconciled fee amounts at lot/transaction level. \n\n#### 2.5. Revenue Recalculation on Rate Card Changes\n\n* When **rate card (trail fee) definitions are modified**, the system allows **revenue recalculation for previous months** from the Revenue Desk, ensuring historical fee income aligns with updated rates and business rules. \n\n\n### 3. How and where fees are applied in journeys and data\n\n1. **At transaction / lot level**  \n   * For each subscription, SIP/STP, switch, or other eligible transaction, the system generates **lots** that are used as the base for trail fee computation over time.  \n\n2. **At customer and AUM reporting level**  \n   * Computed and reconciled trail fees feed into **revenue and AUM dashboards/reports**, with the ability to adjust when rate cards are changed. \n\n3. **At fund house / scheme governance level**  \n   * Fund house and scheme parameters (e.g., eligibility for special fees, B30/T30 applicability, clawback rules) are maintained centrally and govern where and how fee percentages are applied. \n\n\n### 4. Summary\n\n* The platform **primarily supports percentage-based commission/trail fee structures**, including standard trail, location-based additional trail (B30), special trail, and corresponding clawbacks.    \n* Fee definitions are maintained in a **Trail Fee / rate card maintenance module under the Revenue Desk**, with creation, modification, deletion and supervisor authorization workflows.    \n* Scheme and fund-house level maintenance captures **eligibility flags and exclusions**, which govern which fee rules apply to which products and transaction types.   \n* Fees are computed by a **trail fee computation engine** and validated via **trail fee reconciliation** against RTA reverse feeds, capturing brokerage and clawback at lot level.  \n* The documentation available does **not explicitly define flat-fee or generic performance-fee (e.g., profit-sharing) structures**; the implemented and detailed models are all **percentage-based**.\n\n\n#### Sources\n\n1. [1] SBI_Revenue and Reconcilliation_Trail Fee Computation_V10_SBI_CCV11.pdf  \n2. [2] SBI_Journey of Client Portal_Observation SolutioningV10_CCV10.pdf  \n3. [3] SBI_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_Trade Processing_V10_CCV12.pdf', 'b48179e1-5dc3-473b-acd9-6bab9adc7fa2', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["INVESTOR","RM","Order","customer","transaction","Product risk profile","CIF id","securities","warning message","security"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:cif_id"