('274', '105', 'user', 'Which events are audited for immutability across orders, payments, and access?', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-12-18 07:59:21.149948'),
('275', '105', 'assistant', 'Audit events that Cement Immutable Records Across Orders, Payments, and Access\n\n- Access and authentication events (Login and access-control changes): These are captured in the audit trail to provide a tamper-evident history of who accessed the system and when, including the user who performed actions and the timing of those actions, as well as changes to access rights. This is explicitly described in audit-trail documentation, including the login workflow and the general audit-trail framework for access-domain activities. [1] [2]\n\n- Order and payment-related transactional events: The audit trail framework is described as recording actions on key business entities within transactional domains (e.g., PMX-related entities). While specific enumerations vary by module, the PMX audit-trail documentation demonstrates that actions performed on critical transactional entities are logged chronologically, providing an immutable record of changes and actions taken in those domains. Examples of audited PMX entities include Asset Allocation, Security Portfolio, Model Portfolio, Security, and other core items that collectively cover transactional actions and order/payments-related changes within the platform. [4]\n\n- Data fields captured for each audited event (immutability evidence): For every audited entry, the following data are captured to establish a tamper-evident, versioned history: the entity’s unique id, a description of the entity, Maker ID (who created/modified), Maker Date (when created/modified), Auth ID (who authorized), Auth Date (when authorized/rejected), Status (e.g., Unauthorized, Authorized, Rejected, Modified), and Revision ID (a unique revision identifier). These fields underpin immutability and traceability across all audited events. [1]\n\n- Access to audit trails (retrieval and query): The audit-trail UI supports filtering by From Date, To Date, Entity Type, and Entity, enabling users to locate and review audited events across orders, payments, and access-related actions within the defined date windows. This is described across multiple audit-trail documentation sets, illustrating consistent capabilities to query historical audit data by date ranges and entity types. [2] [3]\n\n- Chronological storage of audit data: Audit trail entries are stored chronologically, ensuring a sequential, tamper-evident history of actions. This characteristic is demonstrated in PMX-focused audit-trail documentation, which states that audit information is kept in chronological order and captured for actions performed by users. [4]\n\n\nSources:\n- [1] SBI_Audit Trail_V10.pdf\n- [2] Maybank_Audit Trail_V13_CCV12.pdf\n- [3] HSBC_Audit Trail_V10_CCV10.pdf\n- [4] 360One_Audit Trail_V10_CCV10.pdf', 'b748088d-8c29-4200-bba3-f98577f7bd26', NULL, '{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Order","transaction","RTA Transaction File","Wealth Transactions Tables","Order Book Report","document","Flow Diagram","Login","system generated mail","HSBC PWS"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:order","report:document","dataentity:transaction","system:generated_mail","datastore:rta_transaction_file","report:login","report:flow_diagram","system:hsbc_pws","report:order_book_report","dataentity:login","dataentity:document","datastore:wealth_transactions_tables"],"expanded_nodes":97,"expanded_edges":254,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser''s Question: Which events are audited for immutability across orders, payments, and access?\\n\\nRESPONSE FORMAT:\\nReturn a singl