('282', '107', 'user', 'Synthesize the provided documentation to construct an ''Operational Continuity Strategy'' that mitigates risk during an abrupt RM Handover. Specifically, analyze how the system''s functional logic handles the collision of the following four concurrent workflows, and identify potential ''Process Deadlocks'' or data visibility gaps for the Supervisor', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-12-19 10:13:19.585142'),
('283', '107', 'assistant', '**Operational Continuity Strategy for Abrupt RM Handover**  \n*Domain: Wealth Management – focus on collisions between 4 concurrent workflows*\n\n---\n\n## 1. Handover Context\n\nWhen an RM exits abruptly, the platform’s **Handover** function remaps all clients and pipeline items to a new RM or supervisor. This avoids “ownerless” clients but does **not** by itself resolve in‑flight workflows.\n\nThe continuity strategy must therefore explicitly manage the interaction of these four concurrent workflows:\n\n1. Validations & Warnings (risk controls)  \n2. Supervisor Approval process  \n3. Performance Projection usage  \n4. Mutual Fund / Product Cart order workflow  \n\nand identify where these can collide to create:\n\n- **Process deadlocks** (items stuck with no actor able to move them), and  \n- **Supervisor visibility gaps** (items that exist but are hard to see or interpret).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Workflow 1 – Validations & Warnings\n\n**System logic**\n\n- **Soft stops**  \n  - Trigger warning pop‑ups (e.g., product risk slightly above client risk profile).  \n  - RM can override with justification; system logs deviation.  \n  - On submission, order is routed for higher approval (e.g., Circle/Zonal head, then Supervisor).\n\n- **Hard stops**  \n  - Trigger when a critical rule is breached (e.g., missing mandatory data, product far outside risk profile).  \n  - System **blocks** transaction until corrected.  \n  - Hard‑stop and soft‑stop items are listed in the **Product Cart deviation overlay**.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks during handover**\n\n- **Deadlock 1 – Unresolved hard stops**  \n  - Orders with hard‑stop issues created by the outgoing RM remain blocked.  \n  - If no one takes ownership to correct data or remove the product, the order is stuck indefinitely.\n\n- **Deadlock 2 – Soft‑stop overrides with no follow‑through**  \n  - Outgoing RM may have accepted warnings and submitted orders that still require higher‑level approval.  \n  - If these are not visible or reviewed, risk‑deviant orders may sit in limbo.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Deviations are visible at **order level** (Product Cart overlay), but:  \n  - There is no inherent “RM has left” flag on those deviations.  \n  - If the supervisor only looks at approvals by RM name, they may miss risk‑deviant orders tied to a now‑inactive RM.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Immediate sweep** after RM exit:\n  - Query all orders with:\n    - Hard‑stop deviations outstanding, and  \n    - Soft‑stop deviations accepted but still pending approval.\n- **Reassignment rule**:\n  - New RM or operations user must:\n    - Complete missing data/documents to clear hard stops, or  \n    - Remove non‑compliant products and re‑discuss with client.\n- **Supervisor check**:\n  - Supervisor re‑reviews all soft‑stop overrides from the outgoing RM before approval.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Workflow 2 – Supervisor Approval Process\n\n**System logic**\n\n- Orders submitted by RMs go to **“Pending Approval”**.  \n- Visible in **Supervisor Approval screen**:  \n  - Search by Order No., Scheme/Security, Customer Name.  \n  - Filter by Transaction Type and **RM Name**.  \n- Orders remain in the queue even if the originating RM becomes inactive.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks during handover**\n\n- **Deadlock 3 – Approvals stuck due to reliance on RM filter**  \n  - If the outgoing RM’s profile is disabled, filtering by RM name may no longer be reliable.  \n  - Pending approvals still exist but may not be surfaced if the supervisor relies only on that filter.\n\n- **Deadlock 4 – Multi‑level approvals with absent approver**  \n  - Orders escalated to intermediate approvers (e.g., Circle/Zonal head) can stall if that approver is unavailable and no escalation rule is applied.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Pending orders are visible, but:\n  - They may be “orphaned” conceptually (no active RM to provide context).  \n  - There is no automatic consolidation of “all pending items from RM X who has left” unless the supervisor runs targeted queries.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Standard operating step on RM exit**:\n  - Supervisor runs a **pending approvals report** filtered by:\n    - Outgoing RM ID (if still available), and  \n    - Client IDs reassigned to the new RM.\n- **Escalation SLA**:\n  - Define time‑based rules:\n    - If an order remains in “Pending Approval” beyond X hours/days, it escalates to the next authority.  \n- **No re‑entry rule**:\n  - Orders already submitted by the outgoing RM are **not re‑captured**; they are reviewed and approved/rejected as is, with the new RM informed of context.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Workflow 3 – Performance Projection\n\n**System logic**\n\n- Performance Projection is an **analytical tool**:\n  - Simulates future performance under different scenarios.  \n  - Does not create or hold transactional state by itself.  \n  - Outputs (reports, illustrations) may be used in client discussions.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks**\n\n- No technical deadlock: projections do not block or gate orders.  \n- **Risk is advisory continuity**, not process blockage:\n  - Client may have seen a specific projection or strategy from the outgoing RM that is not documented.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- If projections or proposals are not attached to the client record:\n  - New RM and supervisor may not know what was shown or promised.  \n  - This can lead to inconsistent advice or client confusion.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Documentation rule**:\n  - Any projection used in a client proposal should be:\n    - Saved/attached to the client record, or  \n    - Summarized in client notes.\n- **Onboarding brief**:\n  - Supervisor ensures new RM:\n    - Re‑runs key projections for active opportunities, and  \n    - Aligns recommendations with what the client has already seen.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Workflow 4 – Mutual Funds & Product Cart\n\n**System logic**\n\n- RM builds orders in **Product Cart**:\n  - Product selection, validations, documentation checks, client OTP (if applicable), then submission.  \n- System supports **“Order(s) in Pending State”**:\n  - Partially completed orders can be saved and resumed.  \n- Certain transaction types require **mandatory document upload** before submission.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks during handover**\n\n- **Deadlock 5 – Orders in Pending State with no owner**  \n  - Outgoing RM leaves with partially completed orders saved but not submitted.  \n  - If not reassigned/reviewed, these instructions remain indefinitely in pending state.\n\n- **Deadlock 6 – Mandatory documents not uploaded**  \n  - Orders that require a document (e.g., physical mode redemption/switch) cannot be submitted without upload.  \n  - If the outgoing RM had not obtained/uploaded the document, the order is blocked.\n\n- **Deadlock 7 – Expired or incomplete client authentication (OTP)**  \n  - If OTP was initiated but not completed before RM exit, the transaction attempt expires.  \n  - No one triggers a fresh OTP; the order never progresses.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Pending orders are tied to:\n  - Client ID and (original) RM ID.  \n- Without a targeted review of **“Order(s) in Pending State)”** for the outgoing RM’s clients, the supervisor may not see:\n  - Draft orders,  \n  - Orders awaiting documents, or  \n  - Orders awaiting client action.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Pending bucket sweep**:\n  - On RM exit, operations/supervisor:\n    - Extract all “Order(s) in Pending State” for that RM’s clients.  \n    - Reassign to the new RM.\n- **Action rules** for each pending order:\n  - New RM must:\n    - Confirm with client whether to proceed, modify, or cancel.  \n    - Obtain and upload any mandatory documents.  \n    - Re‑initiate OTP or other client authentication as needed.\n- **Supervisor oversight**:\n  - Supervisor reviews Product Cart deviation overlays for:\n    - Missing documents,  \n    - Hard/soft stops,  \n    - Any “document upload is mandatory” flags.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Cross‑Workflow Collision Analysis\n\nThe four workflows can overlap on the same order or client. Key collision patterns:\n\n1. **Pending Cart + Validations + Approvals**  \n   - Order in Product Cart with:\n     - Hard‑stop deviation unresolved, and  \n     - Not yet submitted for approval.  \n   - If RM leaves, order is stuck in Pending State with no path to approval.  \n   - **Mitigation**: Pending bucket sweep + new RM resolves deviations, then submits for approval.\n\n2. **Soft‑stop Override + Supervisor Approval + RM Exit**  \n   - Outgoing RM overrides a soft stop and submits.  \n   - Order is in supervisor queue with risk deviation.  \n   - If not explicitly reviewed, it may age in the queue.  \n   - **Mitigation**: Supervisor runs targeted report of all pending approvals with deviations from outgoing RM; applies escalation SLA.\n\n3. **Projection‑Driven Proposal + Draft Order**  \n   - RM shows client a projection, starts building a corresponding MF order, saves it, then exits.  \n   - New RM sees only a draft order with no context.  \n   - **Mitigation**: Require projection/proposal notes attached to client record; supervisor briefs new RM on strategy before order completion.\n\n4. **Mandatory Document + Multi‑Level Approval**  \n   - Order requires document upload and higher‑level approval.  \n   - Document not uploaded; RM exits; intermediate approver unavailable.  \n   - **Mitigation**: New RM/ops obtains document; escalation SLA ensures higher authority can approve if intermediate approver is absent.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Supervisor‑Centric Continuity Playbook\n\n**A. Immediate actions on RM exit**\n\n1. **Client & pipeline reassignment**\n   - Execute Handover to assign all clients to new RM/supervisor.\n\n2. **Queue sweeps**\n   - Supervisor/ops to extract:\n     - All **Pending Approval** orders created by outgoing RM.  \n     - All **Order(s) in Pending State)** for outgoing RM’s clients.  \n     - All orders with **hard/soft‑stop deviations** linked to those clients.\n\n3. **Visibility checks**\n   - Use multiple search keys:\n     - Client ID, Order No., Scheme/Security, not just RM name (in case RM profile is disabled).\n\n**B. Deadlock resolution rules**\n\n- **Hard stops**:  \n  - Must be cleared by new RM/ops (data/documents) or product removed.  \n- **Soft stops**:  \n  - Supervisor re‑validates risk acceptance; may request new RM to reconfirm with client.  \n- **Pending approvals**:  \n  - Apply escalation SLA if intermediate approver is unavailable.  \n- **Pending cart orders**:  \n  - New RM contacts client to confirm intent; either complete, modify, or cancel.\n\n**C. Governance & audit**\n\n- **Off‑boarding checklist for RM**:\n  - Confirm:\n    - All pending orders identified and reassigned.  \n    - All key client proposals/projections documented in client records.\n\n- **On‑boarding checklist for new RM**:\n  - Review:\n    - List of pending approvals and pending cart orders.  \n    - Deviations and documents outstanding.  \n    - Client notes and projection reports.\n\n- **Audit trail**:\n  - Use system logs to verify:\n    - Who reassigned orders,  \n    - Who overrode deviations,  \n    - Who approved or cancelled pending items during the handover window.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Summary of Deadlocks & Visibility Gaps\n\n**Potential Process Deadlocks**\n\n1. Orders blocked by **unresolved hard stops**.  \n2. **Pending approvals** tied to an inactive RM or unavailable approver.  \n3. **Pending cart orders** with no active owner.  \n4. Orders requiring **mandatory documents** that were never obtained.  \n5. Transactions with **expired OTP/authentication** not retriggered.\n\n**Potential Supervisor Visibility Gaps**\n\n1. Reliance on **RM‑name filters** when RM profile is disabled.  \n2. Lack of consolidated view of:\n   - All **pending approvals**,  \n   - All **pending cart orders**,  \n   - All **deviation‑bearing orders** for the outgoing RM’s clients.  \n3. Missing documentation of **projections/proposals**, leading to advisory discontinuity.\n\n**Core Strategy**\n\n- Use existing system queues (Pending Approval, Pending State, deviation overlays) as **control points**.  \n- Make supervisor responsible for:\n  - Sweeping these queues on RM exit,  \n  - Reassigning and resolving items,  \n  - Enforcing escalation SLAs.  \n- Ensure all advisory context (projections, risk deviations, documents) is attached to client records so the new RM can continue seamlessly.\n\nThis integrated approach minimizes operational, compliance, and client‑experience risk during an abrupt RM handover.', 'resp_0b60d6027530799e006942515e2a40819fb7ca0284f3e615d7', NULL, '{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"conversation","confidence":1,"matchedKeywords":[]},"jobId":"job_1765953887233_4k0vth05f","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_0b60d6027530799e006942515e2a40819fb7ca0284f3e615d7","reportFormat":"Custom","mode":"deep","answeredAt":"2025-12-19T10:13:19.534Z","isCached":true,"cacheId":101,"cachedSimilarity":0.9999997913837482,"cachedMode":"deep"}', '2025-12-19 10:13:19.692051'),
('284', '108', 'user', 'Synthesize the provided documentation to construct an ''Operational Continuity Strategy'' that mitigates risk during an abrupt RM Handover. Specifically, analyze how the system''s functional logic handles the collision of the following four concurrent workflows, and identify potential ''Process Deadlocks'' or data visibility gaps for the Supervisor', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2025-12-19 10:13:48.660036'),
('285', '108', 'assistant', '**Operational Continuity Strategy for Abrupt RM Handover**  \n*Domain: Wealth Management – focus on collisions between 4 concurrent workflows*\n\n---\n\n## 1. Handover Context\n\nWhen an RM exits abruptly, the platform’s **Handover** function remaps all clients and pipeline items to a new RM or supervisor. This avoids “ownerless” clients but does **not** by itself resolve in‑flight workflows.\n\nThe continuity strategy must therefore explicitly manage the interaction of these four concurrent workflows:\n\n1. Validations & Warnings (risk controls)  \n2. Supervisor Approval process  \n3. Performance Projection usage  \n4. Mutual Fund / Product Cart order workflow  \n\nand identify where these can collide to create:\n\n- **Process deadlocks** (items stuck with no actor able to move them), and  \n- **Supervisor visibility gaps** (items that exist but are hard to see or interpret).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Workflow 1 – Validations & Warnings\n\n**System logic**\n\n- **Soft stops**  \n  - Trigger warning pop‑ups (e.g., product risk slightly above client risk profile).  \n  - RM can override with justification; system logs deviation.  \n  - On submission, order is routed for higher approval (e.g., Circle/Zonal head, then Supervisor).\n\n- **Hard stops**  \n  - Trigger when a critical rule is breached (e.g., missing mandatory data, product far outside risk profile).  \n  - System **blocks** transaction until corrected.  \n  - Hard‑stop and soft‑stop items are listed in the **Product Cart deviation overlay**.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks during handover**\n\n- **Deadlock 1 – Unresolved hard stops**  \n  - Orders with hard‑stop issues created by the outgoing RM remain blocked.  \n  - If no one takes ownership to correct data or remove the product, the order is stuck indefinitely.\n\n- **Deadlock 2 – Soft‑stop overrides with no follow‑through**  \n  - Outgoing RM may have accepted warnings and submitted orders that still require higher‑level approval.  \n  - If these are not visible or reviewed, risk‑deviant orders may sit in limbo.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Deviations are visible at **order level** (Product Cart overlay), but:  \n  - There is no inherent “RM has left” flag on those deviations.  \n  - If the supervisor only looks at approvals by RM name, they may miss risk‑deviant orders tied to a now‑inactive RM.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Immediate sweep** after RM exit:\n  - Query all orders with:\n    - Hard‑stop deviations outstanding, and  \n    - Soft‑stop deviations accepted but still pending approval.\n- **Reassignment rule**:\n  - New RM or operations user must:\n    - Complete missing data/documents to clear hard stops, or  \n    - Remove non‑compliant products and re‑discuss with client.\n- **Supervisor check**:\n  - Supervisor re‑reviews all soft‑stop overrides from the outgoing RM before approval.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Workflow 2 – Supervisor Approval Process\n\n**System logic**\n\n- Orders submitted by RMs go to **“Pending Approval”**.  \n- Visible in **Supervisor Approval screen**:  \n  - Search by Order No., Scheme/Security, Customer Name.  \n  - Filter by Transaction Type and **RM Name**.  \n- Orders remain in the queue even if the originating RM becomes inactive.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks during handover**\n\n- **Deadlock 3 – Approvals stuck due to reliance on RM filter**  \n  - If the outgoing RM’s profile is disabled, filtering by RM name may no longer be reliable.  \n  - Pending approvals still exist but may not be surfaced if the supervisor relies only on that filter.\n\n- **Deadlock 4 – Multi‑level approvals with absent approver**  \n  - Orders escalated to intermediate approvers (e.g., Circle/Zonal head) can stall if that approver is unavailable and no escalation rule is applied.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Pending orders are visible, but:\n  - They may be “orphaned” conceptually (no active RM to provide context).  \n  - There is no automatic consolidation of “all pending items from RM X who has left” unless the supervisor runs targeted queries.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Standard operating step on RM exit**:\n  - Supervisor runs a **pending approvals report** filtered by:\n    - Outgoing RM ID (if still available), and  \n    - Client IDs reassigned to the new RM.\n- **Escalation SLA**:\n  - Define time‑based rules:\n    - If an order remains in “Pending Approval” beyond X hours/days, it escalates to the next authority.  \n- **No re‑entry rule**:\n  - Orders already submitted by the outgoing RM are **not re‑captured**; they are reviewed and approved/rejected as is, with the new RM informed of context.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Workflow 3 – Performance Projection\n\n**System logic**\n\n- Performance Projection is an **analytical tool**:\n  - Simulates future performance under different scenarios.  \n  - Does not create or hold transactional state by itself.  \n  - Outputs (reports, illustrations) may be used in client discussions.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks**\n\n- No technical deadlock: projections do not block or gate orders.  \n- **Risk is advisory continuity**, not process blockage:\n  - Client may have seen a specific projection or strategy from the outgoing RM that is not documented.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- If projections or proposals are not attached to the client record:\n  - New RM and supervisor may not know what was shown or promised.  \n  - This can lead to inconsistent advice or client confusion.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Documentation rule**:\n  - Any projection used in a client proposal should be:\n    - Saved/attached to the client record, or  \n    - Summarized in client notes.\n- **Onboarding brief**:\n  - Supervisor ensures new RM:\n    - Re‑runs key projections for active opportunities, and  \n    - Aligns recommendations with what the client has already seen.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Workflow 4 – Mutual Funds & Product Cart\n\n**System logic**\n\n- RM builds orders in **Product Cart**:\n  - Product selection, validations, documentation checks, client OTP (if applicable), then submission.  \n- System supports **“Order(s) in Pending State”**:\n  - Partially completed orders can be saved and resumed.  \n- Certain transaction types require **mandatory document upload** before submission.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks during handover**\n\n- **Deadlock 5 – Orders in Pending State with no owner**  \n  - Outgoing RM leaves with partially completed orders saved but not submitted.  \n  - If not reassigned/reviewed, these instructions remain indefinitely in pending state.\n\n- **Deadlock 6 – Mandatory documents not uploaded**  \n  - Orders that require a document (e.g., physical mode redemption/switch) cannot be submitted without upload.  \n  - If the outgoing RM had not obtained/uploaded the document, the order is blocked.\n\n- **Deadlock 7 – Expired or incomplete client authentication (OTP)**  \n  - If OTP was initiated but not completed before RM exit, the transaction attempt expires.  \n  - No one triggers a fresh OTP; the order never progresses.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Pending orders are tied to:\n  - Client ID and (original) RM ID.  \n- Without a targeted review of **“Order(s) in Pending State)”** for the outgoing RM’s clients, the supervisor may not see:\n  - Draft orders,  \n  - Orders awaiting documents, or  \n  - Orders awaiting client action.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Pending bucket sweep**:\n  - On RM exit, operations/supervisor:\n    - Extract all “Order(s) in Pending State” for that RM’s clients.  \n    - Reassign to the new RM.\n- **Action rules** for each pending order:\n  - New RM must:\n    - Confirm with client whether to proceed, modify, or cancel.  \n    - Obtain and upload any mandatory documents.  \n    - Re‑initiate OTP or other client authentication as needed.\n- **Supervisor oversight**:\n  - Supervisor reviews Product Cart deviation overlays for:\n    - Missing documents,  \n    - Hard/soft stops,  \n    - Any “document upload is mandatory” flags.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Cross‑Workflow Collision Analysis\n\nThe four workflows can overlap on the same order or client. Key collision patterns:\n\n1. **Pending Cart + Validations + Approvals**  \n   - Order in Product Cart with:\n     - Hard‑stop deviation unresolved, and  \n     - Not yet submitted for approval.  \n   - If RM leaves, order is stuck in Pending State with no path to approval.  \n   - **Mitigation**: Pending bucket sweep + new RM resolves deviations, then submits for approval.\n\n2. **Soft‑stop Override + Supervisor Approval + RM Exit**  \n   - Outgoing RM overrides a soft stop and submits.  \n   - Order is in supervisor queue with risk deviation.  \n   - If not explicitly reviewed, it may age in the queue.  \n   - **Mitigation**: Supervisor runs targeted report of all pending approvals with deviations from outgoing RM; applies escalation SLA.\n\n3. **Projection‑Driven Proposal + Draft Order**  \n   - RM shows client a projection, starts building a corresponding MF order, saves it, then exits.  \n   - New RM sees only a draft order with no context.  \n   - **Mitigation**: Require projection/proposal notes attached to client record; supervisor briefs new RM on strategy before order completion.\n\n4. **Mandatory Document + Multi‑Level Approval**  \n   - Order requires document upload and higher‑level approval.  \n   - Document not uploaded; RM exits; intermediate approver unavailable.  \n   - **Mitigation**: New RM/ops obtains document; escalation SLA ensures higher authority can approve if intermediate approver is absent.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Supervisor‑Centric Continuity Playbook\n\n**A. Immediate actions on RM exit**\n\n1. **Client & pipeline reassignment**\n   - Execute Handover to assign all clients to new RM/supervisor.\n\n2. **Queue sweeps**\n   - Supervisor/ops to extract:\n     - All **Pending Approval** orders created by outgoing RM.  \n     - All **Order(s) in Pending State)** for outgoing RM’s clients.  \n     - All orders with **hard/soft‑stop deviations** linked to those clients.\n\n3. **Visibility checks**\n   - Use multiple search keys:\n     - Client ID, Order No., Scheme/Security, not just RM name (in case RM profile is disabled).\n\n**B. Deadlock resolution rules**\n\n- **Hard stops**:  \n  - Must be cleared by new RM/ops (data/documents) or product removed.  \n- **Soft stops**:  \n  - Supervisor re‑validates risk acceptance; may request new RM to reconfirm with client.  \n- **Pending approvals**:  \n  - Apply escalation SLA if intermediate approver is unavailable.  \n- **Pending cart orders**:  \n  - New RM contacts client to confirm intent; either complete, modify, or cancel.\n\n**C. Governance & audit**\n\n- **Off‑boarding checklist for RM**:\n  - Confirm:\n    - All pending orders identified and reassigned.  \n    - All key client proposals/projections documented in client records.\n\n- **On‑boarding checklist for new RM**:\n  - Review:\n    - List of pending approvals and pending cart orders.  \n    - Deviations and documents outstanding.  \n    - Client notes and projection reports.\n\n- **Audit trail**:\n  - Use system logs to verify:\n    - Who reassigned orders,  \n    - Who overrode deviations,  \n    - Who approved or cancelled pending items during the handover window.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Summary of Deadlocks & Visibility Gaps\n\n**Potential Process Deadlocks**\n\n1. Orders blocked by **unresolved hard stops**.  \n2. **Pending approvals** tied to an inactive RM or unavailable approver.  \n3. **Pending cart orders** with no active owner.  \n4. Orders requiring **mandatory documents** that were never obtained.  \n5. Transactions with **expired OTP/authentication** not retriggered.\n\n**Potential Supervisor Visibility Gaps**\n\n1. Reliance on **RM‑name filters** when RM profile is disabled.  \n2. Lack of consolidated view of:\n   - All **pending approvals**,  \n   - All **pending cart orders**,  \n   - All **deviation‑bearing orders** for the outgoing RM’s clients.  \n3. Missing documentation of **projections/proposals**, leading to advisory discontinuity.\n\n**Core Strategy**\n\n- Use existing system queues (Pending Approval, Pending State, deviation overlays) as **control points**.  \n- Make supervisor responsible for:\n  - Sweeping these queues on RM exit,  \n  - Reassigning and resolving items,  \n  - Enforcing escalation SLAs.  \n- Ensure all advisory context (projections, risk deviations, documents) is attached to client records so the new RM can continue seamlessly.\n\nThis integrated approach minimizes operational, compliance, and client‑experience risk during an abrupt RM handover.', 'resp_0b60d6027530799e006942515e2a40819fb7ca0284f3e615d7', NULL, '{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"conversation","confidence":1,"matchedKeywords":[]},"jobId":"job_1765953887233_4k0vth05f","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_0b60d6027530799e006942515e2a40819fb7ca0284f3e615d7","reportFormat":"Custom","mode":"deep","answeredAt":"2025-12-19T10:13:48.501Z","isCached":true,"cacheId":101,"cachedSimilarity":0.9999997913837482,"cachedMode":"deep"}', '2025-12-19 10:13:48.771242');
